<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister to Stage Public Question Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new Prime Minister Tony
Blair is to take part in 90-minute question-and-answer sessions
with the public in a bid to keep in touch with ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
Downing Street sources were quoted by BBC television as saying
today that the question-and-answer sessions will be held each
month on a Friday and the first experiment session is expected to
start on Friday with the focus on crime.
</P>
<P>
Blair, whose Labor party won a landslide victory on a May 1
election, is committed to staying in touch with ordinary British
citizens and will not become isolated in Westminster (British
parliament), the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Explaining this initiative on Saturday, Blair said: "We have
been elected as New Labor with a set of specific promises to
fulfil. It's our contract with the British people. Like contract,
it's dependent on the satisfaction of both sides."
</P>
<P>
"That's why I want the British people to have the chance
regularly to intervene to make sure we are living up to our
promises," Blair added.
</P>
<P>
Blair has reportedly decided the initial sessions will focus on
the Labor party's main election pledges on health, jobs and crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
