<HEADLINE> Kuwait Hopes Ties With France Remain Solid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait today expressed the hope
that its relations with France, one of the key western countries
signing defense pact with it after the Gulf War, will remain solid
under a new French government.
</P>
<P>
While congratulating the election of Lionel Jospin as the new
French prime minister, Kuwaiti Minister of Cabinet Affairs Abdul
Aziz Dehkil Al-Dekhil said in a statement after a cabinet session
today that Kuwait highlighted Paris "support to Kuwait's just
causes."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has strong military and economic ties with France and
signed a defense pact with France in 1992 similar to agreements
reached with the United States and Britain after the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have carried out a number of joint military
exercises in Kuwait and the Gulf since the pact was signed.
</P>
<P>
France is also one of the major western trade partners of
Kuwait, with French exports to Kuwait in 1995 reaching 761.2
million U.S. dollars while Kuwait exports to France reaching
133.8 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
