<HEADLINE> U.S. to Join Palestinian-Israeli Experts Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Uniteed States is expected to
join the imminent Palestinian-Israeli expert meeting here to
narrow the differences between the two sides on major issues on
top of the Mideast peace crisis, according to the Egyptian Middle
East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Despite difficulties that hinders its convocation, the meeting
will go on as scheduled this evening to discuss the resumption of
the stalled peace talks that broke off in March as Israel broke
ground for Har Homa, a new Jewish neighborhood in disputed Arab
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
As a result of Egypt's last-minute contacts with both sides to
clear the obstacles, a U.S. delegation would take part in the
Cairo meeting as an observer, besides Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak's top aide Osama el-Baz, well-informed sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian meeting of experts would begin by 20:00
hours local time (17:00 GMT), according to the sources here.
</P>
<P>
However, as time slipped away, the Palestinian and Israeli
sides still face some controversial points, especially the
Jerusalem status and halting construction of new settlements.
</P>
<P>
The decision of holding the Palestinian-Israeli expert meeting
was made after a meeting between Yitzhak Molcho, advisor to
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, and Palestinian
National Authority President Yasser Arafat Friday and was
announced here Saturday following talks between Arafat and Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Erekat, Palestinian minister of local government and chief
negotiator, arrived here this afternoon, leading a Palestinian
delegation that includes Hassan Assfour, coordinator of
negotiations affairs, and Marwan Kanafani, advisor to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Beating a note of cautious optimism over the outcome of today's
meeting, Erekat said that "let us meet but without indulging in
optimism."
</P>
<P>
Arafat's political advisor Nabil Abu Radainah said that there
was nothing new up till now on the part of the Israelis who still
refuse to freeze their settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation embarked on the trip to the Egyptian
capital only after Erekat denied a report that Israel had agreed
to a freeze in settlements building.
</P>
<P>
Kanafani said earlier today that Israel had agreed in principle
to halt the Har Homa project.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian sources anticipated that the Israeli delegation
would include Molcho and Dan Navehm, Israeli cabinet secretary.
</P>
<P>
Israeli sources told Israel Radio that there is a possibility
to reach a compromise during today's meeting on "certain
suspension" regarding building of settlements, but these sources
denied reports that Israel has agreed to halt building in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israeli National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, known
for his anti-peace process stance, expressed opposition to the
negotiations between the Israelis and Palestinians under the
auspices of Egypt and said Israel should run its own affairs.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has reportedly proposed a five-point initiative,
including calls for halting the settlements, stopping any change
in the status of Jerusalem, and committing Israel to the peace
accords it signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials said they would agree to return to the
negotiating table if Israel accepted a freeze on settlement
activities until both sides concluded talks on the final status of
the West Bank, including East Jerusalem and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
