<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Global Ivory Summit Faces Hard Choice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The fate of tens of thousands
of elephants will depend on the outcome of disputes at a meeting
to be attended by representatives from 138 countries in Harare,
capital of Zimbabwe, tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The 138 countries are members of the United Nations Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES).
</P>
<P>
Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe, which between them have 175,000
elephants, are leading the charge.
</P>
<P>
They are backed by South Africa which also supports a proposal by
its domestic national parks' managements for a resumption in trade in
white rhinoceros products.
</P>
<P>
The ban on ivory trade was imposed in 1989 after poaching had
reduced Africa's elephant population to 625,000 from 1.3 million
a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
It has since fallen to about 580,000. According to figures
issued by the CITES, Asia is home to about 50,000 elephants.
</P>
<P>
The inclusion of the African elephant on the endangered species
list did not enjoy the support of the countries now seeking a change.
</P>
<P>
Often the elephants there are cramped for space. Zimbabwe, for
instance, is home to 66,000, but its reserves can support 40,000 only.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe and its allies seek a lifting of the ban exclusive to
themselves. Ivory for sale would be got only from natural deaths or
from elephants shot after attacking people or trampling their crops.
</P>
<P>
Ivory stocks sterilised in warehouses are huge, about 3,000
tusks in Zimbabwe, slightly fewer than those in Namibia.
</P>
<P>
The three countries have proposed that the only country to
receive ivory legally should be Japan, where it is primarily used
to carve hankos.
</P>
<P>
A recent CITES panel of exports had a good look at the merits of
all three applications.
</P>
<P>
There were niggles about Botswana's "inadequate" controls over
stocks. Zimbabwe's enforcement of the ban on the ivory trade was
labelled "grossly inadequate".
</P>
<P>
Namibia won high praise and the conclusion was that the proposal
would benefit both elephants and communities.
</P>
<P>
The World Wide Fund for Nature concurred with the conclusion in
principle, but came out in favour of no trade in ivory.
</P>
<P>
Against any lifting of the ban is the London based Environmental
Investigation Agency (EIA), who believes it has been "a huge success"
in saving the African elephants.
</P>
<P>
Southern African conservation ministers noted recently in Windhoek
that opposition to relaxing trade ban comes "mainly from people far
removed from the realities of our wildlife conservation".
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Namibia's Ministry for Environment and Tourism said
his country's elephant population numbers between 6,000 and 9,000, the
most of this century.
</P>
<P>
The ivory ban has been counterproductive, he said, adding:
"elephants were by far the biggest losers".
</P>
<P>
He said the ban stripped elephants outside of national parks of all
value and made them disposable.
</P>
<P>
"CITES completely ignores the most insidious and irreversible
threat to wildlife in the world habitat loss," the spokesman claimed.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, more than half of the elephants
wander outside protected areas. Only if they are seen not to be a
pest, if they are worth more alive than dead, will they survive,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
