<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Delegation Arrives in Cairo for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli negotiation delegation
flew in here this evening for talks with the Palestinians in a
bid to renew full-scale peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Ambassador to Egypt Zvi Mazel hailed the role played
by Egypt to find a way out of the foundered peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The Egyptian role is good," said the ambassador upon
receiving the Israeli delegation, referring to the successive
visits paid by Osama el-Baz, political advisor of Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak, to Tel Aviv and Gaza to help resume
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian-Israeli meeting at experts' level later today
will discuss the basis of resuming negotiations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli team will consist of cabinet secretary Danny
Naveh, Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu's senior aide Yitzhak
Molcho and his new political adviser Uzi Arad, as well as
Foreign Ministry adviser Ya'acov Bardugo.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian delegation headed by Saeb Erekat, Palestinian
minister of local government, arrived earlier today.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation embarked on the trip to the Egyptian
capital only after Erekat denied a report that Israel had agreed
to a freeze in settlements building.
</P>
<P>
The decision on holding the meeting was made after Arafat
conferred with Netanyahu's senior aide Friday and announced
following his meeting with Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
As a result of Egypt's last-minute contacts, a U.S. delegation
is also likely to take part in the Cairo meeting as an observer,
besides Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's top aide Osama el-Baz,
well-informed sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian meeting of experts would begin by
20:00 hours local time.
</P>
<P>
A flurry of consultations between Israeli and Arab leaders and
among Arabs themselves has boosted the view that a way out of the
current deadlock is pending, and that this has to involve a
cessation or slowdown of Israeli settlement building in disputed
areas, including the Har Homa project in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said that Egypt has proposed a five-point
plan, which includes a freeze on any change in the status of
Jerusalem and a ban on Jewish settlement building in the West
Bank for "a sufficient period."
</P>
<P>
In return, the Palestinians would make a firm commitment to
meeting Israel's security demands, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
