<HEADLINE> Cholera-Hit Zanzibar Gives Green Light to Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar government
today gave a green light to continued tourist activities after
an outbreak of cholera.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Ministry of Health said the disease
was already under control and subsiding.
</P>
<P>
The statement, which follows a report that a number of
tourists coming to Zanzibar went down since cholera broke out on
March 28, stressed that vaccination against cholera was not
compulsory in Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
It said tourists could enter Zanzibar without getting vaccines
but it advised that they were free to take oral vaccine against
the disease in their respective countries as an additional
protection.
</P>
<P>
The disease, which has so far killed 31 people and affected
more than 260 others, has compelled the government to close all
restaurants to check the spread of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
However, closure of restaurants has forced tourists who had
lodged in hotels without restaurant facilities to leave Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
The Air Europe plane, which lands in Zanzibar four times a
week, has for three consecutive weeks stopped flying tourists to
Zanzibar for lack of passengers for fear of the killer disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
