<HEADLINE> Palestinian-Israeli Experts Talks Open as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian and Israeli delegations
opened talks here this evening under the auspices of Egypt in a
bid to renew full-scale peace talks that collapsed two months ago.
</P>
<P>
Despite difficulties that hinders its convocation, the meeting
went on as scheduled to discuss the resumption of the stalled
peace talks that broke off in March as Israel broke ground for
Har Homa, a new Jewish neighborhood in disputed Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
It was almost canceled after a Palestinian senior official
said that Israel had agreed to a pause on settlement
construction, an issue at the center of the peace crisis.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's top aide Osama el-Baz took
part as an observer in the meeting that begun at 20:00 hours
local time, according the Egyptian MENA news agency.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Erekat, Palestinian minister of local government and
chief negotiator arrived here this afternoon, leading a
Palestinian delegation that includes Hassan Assfour, coordinator
of negotiations affairs, and Marwan Kanafani, advisor to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Erekat denied any agreement on any issue has preceded the
meeting. "No agreement has been reached with the Israelis so far,
and the gap remains wide," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Palestinians will affirm at today's meeting
the need to restore the peace process to its right track. "The
Israeli government has to red with the israelis so far, and the
gap remains wide," Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
While the chief Palestinian negotiator refused to disclose
when the Cairo meeting would end, reports said that the
Palestinian delegation would leave for Gaza shortly to report to
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat on the
meeting's outcome and the Israeli proposals.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian sources said that if no progress is made
here, a tripartite summit involving the Egyptian, Palestinian and
Israeli leaders would become a possibility.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation, which flew in later, agreed to make
the trip to the Egyptian capital only after Erekat denied a
report that Israel had agreed to a freeze in settlements building.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation included Yitzhak Molcho, advisor to
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Dan Navehm, Israeli
cabinet secretary.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said that Egypt has proposed a five-point
plan, which includes a freeze on any change in the status of
Jerusalem and a ban on Jewish settlement building in the West
Bank for "a sufficient period."
</P>
<P>
In return, the Palestinians would make a firm commitment to
meeting Israel's security demands, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
