<HEADLINE> Foreign Ministers of Balkan Countries to Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers of southeast
European countries will meet tomorrow in Thessaloniki, northern
Greece, to seek ways on how to consolidate stability and peace in
the region and to promote political, economic and social
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Those attending the two-day conference will be the foreign
ministers of Greece, the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia
(FYROM), Bulgaria, Yugoslavia, Romania, as well as the Foreign
Undersecretary of Albania and the Deputy Undersecretary of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Issues to be discussed will include promoting political
cooperation, measures for building security and confidence in the
region, developing economic cooperation and coordinating action
for environmental protection and advancing humanitarian, social
and cultural cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos will give an opening
speech and he is expected to propose the convening of a summit of
the leaders of southeastern Europe and the establishment of a
permanent forum for financial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique is to be issued at the conclusion of the
conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
