<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Envoy Visits Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- British Representative for Cyprus,
Sir David Hannay arrived here today for talks with the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides on the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The British envoy's trip to the region takes place one month
ahead of the U.N.-sponsored direct talks between leaders of the
two Cypriot communities, scheduled to begin on July 9, near New
York.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his arrival, Hannay described as positive the
fact that both rival sides in Cyprus were seeking the
establishment of a bizonal, bi-communal federation in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said there was common ground for the start of direct talks
between the two Cypriot sides, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Hannay is expected to meet President Glafcos Clerides on
Monday and will cross into the Turkish-controlled northern part
of Nicosia to meet the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day stay, the British diplomat will also have
meetings with Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides,
President of the House of Representatives Spyros Kyprianou and
U.N. Resident Representative Gustave Feissel.
</P>
<P>
Hannay will fly on to Athens and Ankara for talks with
government officials of the two countries after his visit to
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops occupied its northern
third in the wake of an Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
