<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot FM Reiterates Position on Purchase of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides stressed here today that the S-300 anti-aircraft
missiles which Cyprus purchased from Russia will come to the
island unless a solution to the Cyprus problem is found.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the Larnaca Airport on his return from
Washington where he held talks with his U.S. counterpart
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides confirmed that the question of the Russian S-300
surface-to-air missiles was raised at the Washington meeting
Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said he had told Albright that the missiles would arrive as
scheduled unless the Cyprus problem is solved or an agreement on
the island's demilitarization is reached, or such progress is
made in efforts toward a solution to meet the security needs of
the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
According to U.S. State Department Spokesman Nicholas Burns,
during the talks, Albright expressed "the U.S. long-standing
disagreement" with the decision by the government of Cyprus to
acquire the S-300 missiles system from Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government decided in January this year to
purchase Russian-made S-300 surface-to-air missile system aimed
at boosting its defense capability.
</P>
<P>
The deal has triggered criticism from the U.S., Britain and
some other countries. Turkey has threatened to strike the
missiles if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides' meeting with Albright took place one month before
the U.N.-sponsored direct talks between leaders of the two
Cypriot communities to find a solution to the protracted Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash are expected to be invited for direct talks by
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan early July near New York.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops occupied its northern
third in the wake of a short-lived coup seeking union with
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
