<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Parliament Meets Under Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Sierra Leone's dissolved
parliament met on Saturday, in defiance of a ban on political
activities, to denounce the two-week-old military coup and called for
the return of ousted civilian President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today, the 50 members of the
80-seat parliament unanimously approved a resolution calling on the
military regime to restore the constitution suspended after the coup
on May 25, during the meeting at the Miatta Conference Hall in
Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Several members of parliament have fled the country in the wake of
the coup.
</P>
<P>
"We the members of parliament unequivocally condemned the overthrow
of the constitutionally elected government of Sierra Leone," the
resolution said.
</P>
<P>
It called for urgent immplementation of the peace accord signed
between Kabbah's government and rebels, who launched the civil war
in 1991 and have now flooded into Freetown at the call of the coup
leaders.
</P>
<P>
"Legitimate grievances of the armed forces of Sierra Leone, the
Revolutionary United Front and all other aggrieved parties must be
immediately addressed," the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the coup leaders have been meeting
civilian politicians of the country, trying to win them over, and have
proposed a government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
So far, no one has accepted, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The coup makers have also sent delegations to west African states
to explain their actions and win support for their cause.
</P>
<P>
There is no report on the military's reaction to the meeting
at the movement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the new military regime has called on the
residents of Freetown to go out to the streets this afternoon to show
their opposition against foreign intervention.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Kamara, spokesman of the ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary
Council (AFRC) was quoted as saying on the state radio: "We are
calling on all Sierra Leoneans in Freetown to take to the streets in
their millions, to demostrate against foreign intervention."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the call was made a day before a proposed
meeting on Monday of the United Nations Security Council to discuss
the Sierra Leonean situation.
</P>
<P>
The AFRC statement, read by the spokesman, suggested that the
meeting would give the go-ahead to the intervention by west African
peace-keeping forces led by Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"If Freetown does not demonstrate against foreign intervention, the
UN and the international community will take this as a support, that
the people of Sierra Leone want foreign intervention," it added.
</P>
<P>
Another report said there were some people gathering at the
national stadium this afternoon, but it could not confirm whether it
was the meeting called on by the military.  enditem

