<HEADLINE> Palestinian-Israeli Experts' Talks End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian and Israeli experts
concluded their two-and-a-half-hour talks here tonight which were
designed to renew full-scale peace talks. But no details were
divulged.
</P>
<P>
Both delegations flew home after the talks.
</P>
<P>
Reporters were kept away in distance as delegates swiftly
walked out of the talks, making no remarks.
</P>
<P>
Despite difficulties that hinder its convocation, the meeting
went on as scheduled in a bid to reopen the peace talks that
collapsed in March as Israel began construction of a settlement
plan in Har Homa, a new Jewish neighborhood in disputed Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held at the request of the Palestinian and Israeli
sides under the auspices of Egypt, was almost canceled after a
Palestinian senior official said that Israel had agreed to a pause
on settlement construction.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's top aide Osama el-Baz took
part as an observer in the meeting that begun at 20:00 hours local
time (17:00 GMT), according the Egyptian MENA news agency.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Erekat, Palestinian minister of local government and
chief negotiator arrived here this afternoon, leading a
Palestinian delegation that includes Hassan Assfour, coordinator
of negotiations affairs, and Marwan Kanafani, advisor to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Erekat denied any agreement on any issue has preceded the
meeting. "No agreement has been reached with the Israelis so far,
and the gap remains wide," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Palestinians would affirm at today's meeting
the need to restore the peace process to its right track.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian sources said that if no progress is made here, a
tripartite summit involving the Egyptian, Palestinian and Israeli
leaders would become a possibility.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation, which flew in later, agreed to make
the trip to the Egyptian capital only after Erekat denied a
report that Israel had agreed to a freeze in settlements building.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli delegation included Yitzhak Molcho, advisor to
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Dan Navehm, Israeli
cabinet secretary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
