<HEADLINE> Irish Opposition Wins Narrow Election Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Ireland's main opposition alliance,
including the Fianna Fail and the Progressive Democrats, has
snatched a cliffhanger election victory by snatching 81 of the 166
seats in the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, the Fianna Fail leader Bertie Ahern, who is set to
become the country's new Prime Minister, is expected to have to
woo some support from smaller parties or independents in an effort
to form a working majority in parliament.
</P>
<P>
Ahern was quoted by press reports from Dublin as saying that he
was confident that the parliament would elect him as Ireland's new
Prime Minister when it reconvenes on June 26.
</P>
<P>
But he ruled out the possibility of enlisting electoral support
from Sinn Fein, the political wing of Irish Republican Army (IRA)
guerrillas, which won one seat and will take its place in the
Irish parliament for the first time since the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
On the future tasks of the new government, Ahern said that
three government priorities were "to cut taxes, cut crime and work
for a Northern Ireland settlement."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, final results indicated that Prime Minister John
Bruton's three-party ruling coalition, which won 75 seats in the
election, would have no chance to stay in power. No Irish
government has won an re-election since 1969.
</P>
<P>
The fall of the so-called ruling "Rainbow Coalition" seems to
be triggered by the poor performance of Bruton's main election
partner Labor leader Dick Spring.
</P>
<P>
Labor Party, which is the country's third largest political
party and won 32 seats in 1992 election, suffered a crashing
defeat by losing 15 seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
