<HEADLINE> Iraq Strives to Resume Trade Ties With Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has taken measures to resume
trade ties with Syria by buying Syrian food and re-opening customs
offices on the border with Syria, according to the Iraqi News
Agency (INA).
</P>
<P>
INA today quoted Hameed Shukur Mahmoud, director general of
Iraqi Customs Authority, as saying that Iraq has taken measures
to reopen two customs offices on the border with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud said that these measures come within the requirements
of implementing the contracts signed between Iraq and Syrian
companies under the "oil-for-food" deal which allows Iraq to sell
oil in order to buy food and medicine urgently needed in the
country.
</P>
<P>
A Syrian business delegation paid a visit to Iraq last week and
signed with Iraq a number of commercial contracts to supply the
Iraqis with food and other daily necessities under the
"oil-for-food" deal signed by Baghdad and the U.N. in May last
year.
</P>
<P>
According to these contracts, Syria will export to Iraq 5,000
tons of chick-pea, 3,000 tonnes of soap, 4,000 tonnes of washing
powder and 6,000 tonnes of olive oil.
</P>
<P>
These are the first contracts signed between the two countries
after a 17-year interruption of their trade ties.
</P>
<P>
Iraq severed all its ties with Syria in 1980 since the breakout
of the Iraq-Iran War as Damascus sided with Tehran during the
8-year-long war.
</P>
<P>
The relations between the two neighbors have further worsened
after Syrian troops joined in the 1991 Gulf War against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Later last month, a Syrian trade and industrial delegation,
the first one in the past 17 years, paid a historic visit to
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad hopes for the resumption of Iraq-Syria ties to return
to "their normal situation" as before, an Iraqi official told INA
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sa'd Qassim Hammoudi, chairman of the Arab and International
Relations Committee at the National Assembly, said that "the interests
of the two brotherly countries (Iraq and Syria) necessitates the
return of their ties to the normal situation not only in the
trade and economic fields but also in other aspects."
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi trade delegation is expected to visit Damascus on
mid-June to "carry out more contracts" with Syrian companies,
according to INA. A re-opening of the borders is likely to be
announced during the delegation's visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> List of Sri Lanka's New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga announced her cabinet reshuffle today. The following
is the list of the cabinet members:
</P>
<P>
Ratnasiri Wickremanayake, Minister of Public Administration,
</P>
<P>
 Home Affairs and Plantation Industries
</P>
<P>
Lakshman Jayakody, Minister of Buddha Sasana
</P>
<P>
Lakshman Jayakody, Minister of Cultural and Religious Affairs
