<HEADLINE> Training Leaders For China's State-Owned Enterprises Stressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Wu Bangguo, Chinese vice premier
and member of the Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) Central Committee, emphasized the importance of a three-year
program for training executives and officials of key state-owned
enterprises, when he spoke at the opening ceremony of one of the
courses at the Party School of the CPC Central Committee here
today.
</P>
<P>
Wu called it an important means of improving the management and
Party building in the enterprises and said that, "improving the
leadership of state-owned enterprises ensures the Party's
political guidance in them and It is demanded by reforms and
development."
</P>
<P>
The general assessment of state-owned enterprises' leaders will
be an important job this year, he said, and the assessment will be
based on appraisals by both higher authorities and the employees.
</P>
<P>
He said that training leaders of state-owned enterprises should
combine the study of Deng Xiaoping's theory of building socialism
with Chinese characteristics, the Party's basic line, and the
Party Central Committee's and the State Council's guidelines and
policies on reform and development of state-owned enterprise with
a socialist market economy, new technology, and management
techniques.
</P>
<P>
"Its aim is to improve the overall political quality and
professional management standards of officials of these
enterprises," Wu explained, emphasizing improved supervision of
state-owned enterprises, because many cases of inefficient
management are caused by out-moded ideas, lack of professionalism,
internal quarrels, and even corruption.
</P>
<P>
To improve supervision, he said, the role of Party committees,
boards of directors, boards of supervisors, and the workers'
congresses should be brought into full play.  
</P>
</TEXT>
