<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: Palestinians, Israelis to Meet Again Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian and Israeli experts will
resume negotiations within the next few days on reviving the
deadlocked peace process, Egyptian presidential political advisor
Osama el-Baz said today.
</P>
<P>
"They will meet again in the coming few days, with the active
participation of Egypt, to reach agreement on the major
contentious issues," Baz told the Egyptian Middle East News Agency
(MENA).
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators met here on Sunday night
for the first time in nearly three months in a bid to renew
full-scale peace talks that were paralyzed when Israel began
construction on a new Jewish settlement in the disputed Arab East
Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Baz, who has been shuttling between the sides trying to revive
peacemaking, attended the talks as an observer.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which were held within a positive and constructive
spirit, made "some progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The two delegations have seriously sought to narrow the gap
that divides them and they have managed to reach some progress,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting that lasted for over two hours was chaired by chief
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and Israeli cabinet secretary
Dannay Naveh.
</P>
<P>
The delegations left immediately after the talks to brief the
Israeli government and the Palestinian National Authority over the
results. They later joined Egypt in hailing the good atmosphere
and progress at the Cairo meeting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian officials have confirmed that the fate
of the housing project was discussed in the Egyptian-brokered
talks.
</P>
<P>
They said another Palestinian-Israeli meeting with the
participation of Egypt will be held in Israel on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has intensified its mediation efforts in the crisis since
a summit between Mubarak and Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu last month.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is pushing a five-point plan which would include a freeze
on any change in the status of Jerusalem and a ban on the Jewish
settlement building in the West Bank for "a sufficient period." In
return the Palestinians would give a firm commitment to addressing
Israel's security demands.
</P>
<P>
Israel reportedly has hatched a face-saving compromise under
which it will slow down the construction of the settlement in East
Jerusalem to a near halt to allow the resumption of talks with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
So far Netanyahu has refused to stop the construction for fear
that such a move will tear his right-wing coalition apart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
