<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Epic About Hong Kong Premieres in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The movie "Opium War", which tells
about the British war of aggression against China from 1840 to
1842, premiered in Beijing today, as part of the festivities
for the return of Hong Kong to the motherland on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Following the war, Britain forced the Qing Dynasty to sign an
unfair treaty and grabbed Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Among the audience were Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen and
State Councillor Li Tieying.
</P>
<P>
The production of the film cost more than 80 million yuan (9.6
million US Dollars), and was done by a team of directors from
China's inland areas, Hong Kong, and Taiwan, headed by Xie Jin,
one of China's most successful film directors.
</P>
<P>
"The aim of shooting such a movie is to remind all Chinese of
the past. For any nation, ignorance of the outside world means
backwardness, and a backward country is doomed to be bullied,"
said the 74-year-old Xie.
</P>
<P>
Sun Jiazheng, the minister of Radio, Film and Television,
called it an epic movie. "Only when a country really stands equal
to other nations, can she look her past humiliations in the face,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Liu Mingqi, vice-director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs
Office of the State Council, said the movie provides all the
Chinese people with a good chance for patriotic education,
especially the younger generation.
</P>
<P>
Xie Jin and his crew started filming last May. Over 50,000
people, including 3,000 foreigners, appeared in it. More than
20,000 sets of clothing and 20,000 props were made for the movie,
and 47 ships were made or rehabilitated for the film.
</P>
<P>
"The Opium War" is scheduled for 300 cinemas in 14 cities. The
republic of Korea, Japan, Germany and Italy have also bought the
right to show the movie.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
