<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian President Visits Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- President of the Republic of
Bosnia-Herzegovina Alija Izetbegovic said here today that peace
would never be implemented fully unless war crimes ended.
</P>
<P>
Izetbegovic made the remarks at a ceremony held by his Turkish
counterpart Suleyman Demirel to welcome him in the presidential
palace.
</P>
<P>
Izetbegovic, who arrived here Sunday evening for a two-day
official visit to Turkey, said there were several problems in
implementing the Bosnian Peace Agreement (Dayton Agreement),
adding that several countries were trying to change the agreement
or to implement it only partly.
</P>
<P>
After the four-year civil war in Bosnia, Dayton Agreement was
signed in December 1995 by the leaders of the warring parties on
the division of territory, war criminals, releasing prisoners of
war and repatriating refugees.
</P>
<P>
"we want all the articles of the Dayton agreement to be
implemented fully and we want the refugees to return to their
homes and war criminals to be tried," said Izetbegovic.
</P>
<P>
He added that he came to Turkey to brief the leaders of the
country on the recent situation in Bosnia and exchange views with
them, because Turkey is an important power and a member of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
In response, Demirel said that Turkey supported
Bosnia-Herzegovina even in their difficult days and will continue
to do so.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish head of state said: "Clashes ended, elections took
place in the country, and joint institutions have been
established. Thus, the Bosnian people are able to heal the wounds
of war. Yet, the peace installed in Bosnia-Herzegovina should be
long-lasting."
</P>
<P>
He said Turkey would do its best to contribute for the
implementation of the Dayton agreement, for the preservation of
peace and the creation of atmosphere for stability and
restructure of the Bosnia-Herzegovina's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
