<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Refutes Slander on China's Freedom of Religious Belief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese official cited a series
of facts to refute some Westerners' slander on the freedom of
religious belief in China at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
"China's policy of the freedom of religious belief has been
supported and welcomed by the broad masses of the religious people
in the country, and has been praised by many personnel in the
international community," said Ye Xiaowen, director of the Bureau
of the Religious Affairs under the State Council.
</P>
<P>
But in recent years, some Westerners have turned a blind eye to
the fact that there are hundreds of millions of religious people
and thousands of religious organizations in China which are
engaging in a large number of normal religious activities, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
With ulterior motives, they called the Chinese government's
crackdown on the activities of a small number of cults, which
threatened the social and public interests, "persecution of
religious people" and "intolerance of religion", he said.
</P>
<P>
In truth, since the 1980s, a group of cults have formed in some
places around China, he said, adding that though small in number,
they have greatly harmed Chinese society, and aroused hatred from
both the ordinary people and the religious people.
</P>
<P>
He cited Wu Yangming, who founded the "the Established King
Sect" in east China's Anhui Province as an example, saying that Wu
spread heresy, and claimed that his group will "unite the country
in the spirit of the "the Established King Sect".
</P>
<P>
Wu, in collusion with other key members of the organization,
have seduced and raped 19 young women, the youngest of whom is
only 14 years old, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
The sentence of Wu and his partners by the Chinese judicial
departments drew applause and the deep gratitude of the local
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
In China, people who do not believe in any religion as well as
those who do, have the same rights and obligations under the law
and no one is granted special privileges, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
The religious cults and their actions, which proved dangerous
to society and the public welfare, were punished to safeguard the
people and the sanctity of the law and to maintain social order,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
It is groundless and creates suspicion when some people attack
China's crackdown on criminals by saying that it "persecutes
religious people", he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
