<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President Reshuffles Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga reshuffled her cabinet today, according to a new
release from the president's office.
</P>
<P>
This is the first cabinet reshuffle since Kumaratunga's
People's Alliance (PA) coalition came to power in November 1994.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle expanded the number of ministers to 29 from 23.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga retained the portfolios of defense,
finance and planning.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike, the president's mother,
and Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar retained their posts.
</P>
<P>
Srimani Athulathmudali, leader of the Democratic United
National front, was removed from the cabinet and her portfolio
transport, environment and women's affairs.
</P>
<P>
Some portfolios were interchanged between ministers and eight
new faces inducted into the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Among them, Mahinda Rajapakse, former minister of labor and
vocational training, became minister of fisheries and aquatic
resources to replace Indika Gunawardene who now is minister of
housing and urban development.
</P>
<P>
Former minister of housing, construction and public utilities
Nimal Siripala De Silva was appointed minister of health and
indigenous medicine.
</P>
<P>
Amarasiri Dodangoda, former minister of cooperatives,
provincial councils and indigenous medicine, was appointed
minister of vocational training and rural industries.
</P>
<P>
The president gave the media portfolio to Minister of Posts and
Telecommunications Mangala Samaraweera.
</P>
<P>
According to informed sources, the main objective of the
reshuffle is to raise government working efficiency and speed up
the economic development in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
