<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Government to Guarantee Religious Freedom of HK Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The director-general of the State
Council's Religious Affairs Bureau, Ye Xiaowen, said at a press
conference here today that it will not send a single employee to
Hong Kong or apply the religious laws and regulations of China's
inland areas to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's religious affairs will be managed by the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) government in accordance with
the Basic Law, and his bureau will not intervene in them, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, religious organizations in the Hong
Kong SAR and other parts of China should abide by the principle of
no subordination, no interference, and mutual respect, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We support friendly exchanges between the two places on the
basis of the above-mentioned principles, so as to consolidate and
develop friendly contacts between the religious communities in the
two places," Ye said.
</P>
<P>
Religious activities by the people of Hong Kong in other parts
of China should follow local laws and regulations, and people from
other areas should respect Hong Kong's religions, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
