<HEADLINE> Dollar Plunges to Low for Year in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar dropped to 111.80 yen
this afternoon, its lowest point this year on the Tokyo Foreign
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The drop stems from fear of renewed trade friction between
Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was trading at 112.25-31 yen at 5 p.m., down from
113.18-21 yen at 9 a.m. today, and from 114.25-35 yen late Friday
in New York.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and other U.S. officials
expressed concern over the dollar last Friday, discouraging
investors and sending the key Nikkei average down almost 260
points.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average, 223 selected issues on the First Section of
the Tokyo Stock Exchange, closed at 20,223.82, a dip of 261.93
points or 1.28 percent from last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all issues on the
First Section, fell 4.74 points or 0.31 percent to 1,504.92.
</P>
