<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Introducing Chinese History to the Public in HK (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- When an exhibition on the Chinese
 postal history opens in the Town Hall of Shatin in July this
year, Hong Kong people will be able to see valuable exhibits from
the China Museum of Stamps.
</P>
<P>
This is part of efforts made by the Museums Section of the
Regional Services Department to educate Hong Kong people on the
Chinese history and culture.
</P>
<P>
"Now Hong Kong is about to return to the motherland, it's time
for Hong Kong people to get better acquainted with the Chinese
history and culture and to know more about Hong Kong's history and
 culture," Shui Yuen Yim, Chief Curator of the Museums Section,
said in an exclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Yim is now in charge of the preparatory work for the Hong Kong
Museum of Culture, which is being constructed and scheduled for
opening in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Due to historical reasons, Hong Kong students can find little
information about the history of Hong Kong and the mainland in
their textbooks and actually they know more foreign history than
that of Hong Kong and the mainland. Now it's time to make up the
missed lesson," Yim said.
</P>
<P>
"Every place has its own history. We are the provider of
cultural services, and it's our task to introduce our own history
and culture to the public," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong now has four small museums which are all
housed in age-old buildings. They have many limitations in both
capacities and styles, and it is necessary to build a large modern
 museum.
</P>
<P>
The new museum is designed to reflect the history and culture
of Hong Kong and the mainland, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has over 6,000 years of history, which is evidenced
with the unearthed relics in recent years, and the problem is that
 we've not paid enough attention that it deserves," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said material civilization brings changes to Hong Kong day
by day, and people tend to demolish the old and set up the new. As
 a result, it's hard to preserve valuable historical items, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to collecting those items and handing them
down to future generations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991 when preparations for the museum started, Yim and
his colleagues have collected more than 50,000 pieces of
historical and cultural relics, of which some 6,000 pieces came
from the New Territories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Switzerland Sign Customs Cooperation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
Switzerland today signed a customs agreement to combat smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed on the periphery of the EU finance
ministers' meeting in Luxembourg, is due to come into force on
July 1. It is being added, in the form of a protocol, to a 1972
Free Trade Agreement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The main aim is to mount a coordinated campaign against
fraudulent cross-border operations during goods transit activities.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland was the only major European country with whom the
EU did not have such an agreement. The agreement fills a gap in
the network of legal provisions the EU has been putting in place
since 1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Introducing Chinese History to the Public in HK (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"A Museum is a public institute that has close relations with
the society. The sole purpose of our museum is to raise the
cultural level of Hong Kong people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Folk art constitutes a significant part in Yim's collections.
</P>
<P>
"Other museums usually spend most of their money on protecting
highly-valuable refined relics, but folk art, which is equally
valuable in reflecting history, does not enjoy sufficient
protection and attention, and many are disappearing with the
passing away of the older generation," Yim said.
</P>
<P>
Yim has been visiting the inland areas fairly frequently to
collect folk art items that he believes are valuable, such as
paper-cut, Lunar New Year paintings and kites.
</P>
<P>
"I'd rather buy hundreds of pieces of folk art than buying one
single expensive unearthed relic with the same sum of money. They
may be quite usual in the eyes of some people, but I dare say that
 in 10 years' time they will demonstrate their value," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yim said that he and his colleagues have had very close
cooperation with Mainland counterparts. In the past few years the
Museums Section held four major historical and cultural relics
exhibitions with exhibits on loan from Mainland museums.
</P>
<P>
"To put on show a piece of Chinese cultural relics in Hong Kong
 is quite special--more special than put it on show in any other
place, because we are using it to arouse Hong Kong people's
interest in knowing about China," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the handover of Hong Kong provides them with
abundant opportunities to make good use of the rich resources of
historical and cultural relics in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
The museum includes halls of different themes such as Chinese
Culture, History of the New Territories, Guangdong Opera, Modern
Hong Kong Art and Design and Folk Art.
</P>
<P>
Located in the center of Shatin New Town, the museum is
designed into a Chinese siheyuan-style building. It costs about
800 million HK dollars (102.56 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Yim studied history in the Chinese University of Hong Kong,
Oxford University and Ohio State University. He joined the Museums
 Section in 1987 after serving seven years in a government
department for preserving historical buildings and relics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
