<HEADLINE> 2,850 km Walk From Hong Kong to Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Seventeen people arrived in
Beijing's Tian'anmen Square today after a 2,850-km trip on foot
from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The trip started in February at Shatin Park in Hong Kong's New
Territories.
</P>
<P>
Through the activity, the travellers plan to raise 20 million
HK dollars (2.56 million US dollars) from the Hong Kong residents
to aid school dropouts in poor parts of China. The activity is
sponsored by the Hong Kong Planters Movement, which was founded in
1992.
</P>
<P>
The participants have walked through the provinces of
Guangdong, Hunan, Hubei, Henan, and Hebei where they visited poor
areas, publicizing "Project Hope" along the way, an activity begun
by the Chinese government to help poor children go to school.
</P>
<P>
A torch, which was lit at the starting ceremony in Shatin Park,
was handed to college students from Beijing on June 7, when the
travellers entered the city limits.
</P>
<P>
On the morning of June 12, they will head for the Great Wall at
Badaling, north of Beijing, with 250 people from Hong Kong, who
have been supporting them on the trip.
</P>
<P>
Planters Movement has organized three Walk-to-Guangzhou
activities since it was founded and has raised more than 15
million HK dollars for more than 100 schools in mountainous areas
of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
