<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said today that he had consulted with top leaders
of Egypt and France about possible asylum for former Zairean
president Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiations are still going on to find a country that would
accept him (Mobutu)," Mandela told reporter in Cape Town, the
legislative capital of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mandela declined to give details about his Sunday
consultations with his Egyptian counterpart Hosni Mubarak, French
President Jacques Chirac and Premier Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's top aide Parks Mankahlana told press last week that
political asylum for Mobutu was not the problem at this stage as
the primary consideration was to find an appropriate place for
Mobutu to receive medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu, who is suffering from prostate cancer, is reportedly
living with a large entourage in a luxury hotel, 20 kms outside
the Moroccon capital, Rabat.
</P>
<P>
The deposed president arrived in Morocco on May 23 from Togo
where he had taken refuge from attacks by the armed forces of
Laurent Kabila, now the renamed Democratic Republic of Congo's
president.
</P>
<P>
The Moroccan government said then that Mobutu had come for
just a "brief stay" before going into permanent exile elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu's final destination at the time was believed to be
France, where he owns a lavish villa. 
