<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Commemorating Chinese Writer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong province in south China
is holding a series of activities this week in memory of Lu Xun
(1881--1936), one of China's most famous writers, thinkers, and
revolutionaries.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition of calligraphy and painting marking the 70th
anniversary of his stay in Guangdong, where he was a professor at
Zhongshan University from January to September of 1927, opened
Sunday as the start of the series.
</P>
<P>
In April, 1927, a purge ordered by the head of the Kuomintang
Chiang Kai-shek (1887--1875) led to the deaths of many
communists. Outraged by Chiang's cruelty, Lu lent his support to
the Communist Party, although he never became a member of it.
</P>
<P>
The memorial series includes seminars and discussions. One
seminar is being held in Jiangmen city on "Lu Xun and the 21st
century" and "Lu Xun and study on Hong Kong and Macao."
</P>
<P>
Students will have an opportunity to hear reports on Lu Xun and
his literary ideas at Zhongshan University, South China Normal
University, and the Guangdong Museum.
</P>
<P>
The activities are being organized by the Guangdong Federation
of Literary and Art Circles, the Lu Xun Society of China, and the
Guangdong Society of Lu Xun. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
