<HEADLINE> HK Telecom Expects Flood of Phone Calls on Handover Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Telecom has upgraded
its system and conducted emergency exercises in anticipation of a
flood of phone calls in the hours around the handover ceremony at
midnight June 30.
</P>
<P>
The company believes that phone calls will surge greatly as
people make social arrangements or exchange good wishes with
friends at the historical moment.
</P>
<P>
Today's South China Morning Post reported that this massive
traffic may mean that some customers will have to try 10 times
before getting a dial tone.
</P>
<P>
"We are anticipating traffic will be higher than anything in
history," said Peter Yu Kwok-chu, manager of Local Operations
Branch.
</P>
<P>
Overseas phone companies have been warned to expect a flood of
calls to and from Hong Kong and alternative international routings
 have been planned if certain cables and satellite links are
overloaded.
</P>
<P>
The local network has been upgraded, particularly in the Wan
Chai area where most of the handover activities and the estimated
8,000 journalists will be concentrated.  
</P>
