<HEADLINE> Mubarak Hails Israeli-Palestinian Cairo Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said
today that the Palestinians and Israelis held "promising" talks
here Sunday on the resumption of deadlocked peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the wheel of talks between the two sides will run as
any delay is detrimental to both parties," Mubarak told reporters
at the end of his visit to Qaroun oil fields, some 80 kilometers
south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators met Saturday for the first
time in nearly three months in a bid to renew full-scale peace
talks that were paralyzed when Israel began construction on a new
Jewish settlement in March.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak refused to say whether the meeting was held on certain
or specified bases, but said the atmosphere prevailing it was
"good."
</P>
<P>
"The two parties will consult with their leaderships and we will
see if they will meet within days or later but in general we
are supporting the peace drive to the end," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian officials have confirmed that the fate
of the housing project was discussed in the Egyptian-brokered
talks.
</P>
<P>
They said another Palestinian-Israeli meeting with the
participation of Egypt will be held in Israel on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Osama el-Baz, Mubarak's political advisor who shuttled between
the sides trying to revive peacemaking, attended the talks as an
observer. He said the talks made "some progress."
</P>
<P>
The negotiators did not speak to reporters at the end of the
meeting but they later joined Egypt in hailing the good atmosphere
and progress at the Cairo meeting.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has intensified its mediation efforts in the crisis since
a summit between Mubarak and Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu last month.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was pushing a five-point plan which would include a
freeze on any change in the status of Jerusalem and a ban on the
Jewish settlement building in the West Bank for "a sufficient
period." In return the Palestinians would give a firm commitment
to addressing Israel's security demands.
</P>
<P>
So far Netanyahu has refused to stop Jewish settlements
construction for fear that such a move would tear his right-wing
coalition apart. But the Palestinians said only a freeze to the
settlement construction would help revive the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
