<HEADLINE> Japanese Papers Wary About Defense Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Leading Japanese newspapers said
today that operations cited in the newly released interim report
on Japan-United States defense cooperation may violate the
Constitution, which bans participation in collective defense
activities.
</P>
<P>
The papers called for efforts to gain the understanding of the
Japanese people and Japan's neighboring countries when reviewing
the 1978 Japan-U.S. defense cooperation guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the U.S. worked out the interim report through
high-level talks Saturday in Honolulu. They will finalize the
review this autumn.
</P>
<P>
The Asahi Shimbun said operations such as rear logistic support
by Japan's Self-Defense Forces, minesweeping operations to help
the U.S. military, providing the U.S. military on combat
operations with intelligence and ammunition, and the inspection
of vessels of other nations on the high seas surrounding Japan,
which were all proposed in the report, may be unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
"Such changes in policy should not proceed without national
consensus," the Asahi said.
</P>
<P>
The constitutional ban on collective self-defense rights, and
on the use of force to settle international disputes, contributes
to the trust of East Asian countries in Japan and the stability of
the region, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Mainichi Shimbun said the interim report steps into gray
areas edging close to participation in collective defense.
</P>
<P>
There were too many unclear elements concerning the definition
of areas for rear support of the U.S. military in combat
operations, the Mainichi said.
</P>
<P>
The leading business daily, Nihon Keizai Shimbun, said it is
important to secure transparency in debates on the review in order
to seek the understanding of Japan's neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
