<HEADLINE> China's Longest Suspension Bridge Opens to Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A bridge with a center span of
888 meters over the Pearl River at Humen in Guangdong Province in
south China, the longest suspension bridge in China, opened to
traffic today.
</P>
<P>
The bridge shortens the distance between the special economic
zones of Shenzhen and Zhuhai by 100 km., local officials say, and
it will boost economic development in the Pearl River Delta and
bring Guangdong, Hong Kong, and Macao into a closer relationship.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-premier Zou Jiahua cut the ribbon today at the
opening ceremony. Construction work on the bridge started in
October of 1992. It was built at a cost of three billion yuan
(about 361 million US dollars). 
</P>
