<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Anti-landmines Art Exhibition Ends in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Cai Guozhong)
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- An anti-landmines art exhibition
as part of the global campaign to ban the production, export and
use of anti-personnel mines ended here today at Sheraton Hotel
gardens.
</P>
<P>
Muwonge Willson, an official of Uganda Red Cross Society said
the exhibition was welcomed by enthusiastic Ugandan visitors so
much that it had to be prolonged for another two days.
</P>
<P>
The ten-day exhibition of sculptures by Kenyan artist Kioko
Mwitiki, one of Kenya's leading sculptors, has attracted over
70,000 visitors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 25 sculptures dubbed "living metal" also showed this
year's theme of the pan African movement -- peace and unity.
</P>
<P>
Mwitiki who has done sculptures in Montana, U.S.A and held
private fund-raising in the same place during the exhibition
presents a bigger-than-life music band comprising sculptural
pieces made of iron sheets or bars available from destroyed
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
They include players strumming guitars, drumming and singing
in straining vocal chords about the need to ban landmines,
Willson explained, adding that some empty chairs in front of the
band mean the audience are not listening because some people in
the world are still producing and using anti personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
Mwitiki said, "the inspiration for the exhibition is out of a
desire to help stop the misery caused by the landmines."
</P>
<P>
According to materials available in the exhibition, over 100
million landmines are inflicting appaling sufferings on
individuals, families and their communities in more than 70
countries over the world, with over 30 million scattered across
at least 18 countries in Africa alone.
</P>
<P>
These mines kill and maim 2,000 people monthly across four
continents in the world. Among them, civilians are the most.
</P>
<P>
From 1985 to March 1995, the International Committee of the
Red Cross (ICRC) hospitals and surgical teams treated over 30,000
victims of landmines world wide.
</P>
<P>
In Uganda, landmines have extensively been used by the rebel
Lord's Resistance Army led by Joseph Kony in the north. This has
left thousands of innocent people in northern Uganda either dead
or maimed.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the terrible injuries to human beings, the
landmines prevent farmers from sowing crops, hinder relief
efforts, and generally place an impossible strain on economies
trying to recover from armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Due to all these, the ICRC, the United Nations and other
influential organizations in 1994 launched a campaign demanding a
total ban on landmines' manufacture stockpiling, transfer and use
and since then more than 50 governments have committed themselves
to the ban.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan exhibition supported by the ICRC is spearheading a
world wide campaign for the abolition of landmines.
</P>
<P>
It followed a highly successful one held in Kenya at the end
of March this year and is going for Angola where there are
estimated over 10 million landmines left during the civil war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Stock Market Active in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) in
1996 recorded a transaction of 882 million shares worth of 7.063
billion Naira (about 83 million U.S. Dollars), the Nigerian
Tribune reported today.
</P>
<P>
Pascal Dozie, former president of NSE, disclosed this at the
36th annual general meeting of the exchange, which was held in
Lagos last week.
</P>
<P>
Dozie noted that this performance represented an increase of
122.2 percent over 1995 in volume term, and a growth of 284
percent in value term.
</P>
<P>
The renowned banker attributed the impressive growth to the
on-going operational upgrading efforts at the exchange.
</P>
<P>
Such efforts include a review of the allocation system on the
trading floors, introduction of five percent movement limit,
reduction of the settlement period from a fortnight to a week.
</P>
<P>
The NSE all-share index also grew by 37 percent from 5092.15
in 1995 to 6992.10 in 1996, Dozie said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the International Finance Corporation (IFC), emerging
market data base started producing investible index for the
Nigerian stock market in addition to the IFC global composite
index for the market.
</P>
<P>
According to Dozie, Nigeria, Zimbabwe and South Africa are the
only three countries in Africa with IFC investible index, which
generally guides investors in making investment decisions on any
market.
</P>
<P>
Activities in the new issues market is also on the upward
trend, he said, adding that 37 applications for new issues valued
at 21.5 billion Naira (about 253 million Dollars) were approved
for listing in 1996.
</P>
<P>
For the continued growth of the market, the former NSE called
on the government to constitute the Nigerian Investment Promotion
Commission as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The decree for the establishment of the commission was
approved by the government in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
