<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swaziland Strives for More Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Swaziland government has
tabled a bill introducing new investment incentives in a bid to
attract more investment and boost the manufacturing sector in
particular, according to informed sources reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The Investment Promotion Bill will lead to a reduction in the
corporate tax rate from 37.5 percent to 30 percent during the
current year. Another five percent decrease will be phased in
over the next five years, bringing the rate to 25 percent, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The bill aims broadly to promote new investment, protect
existing investments and facilitate the settlement of investment
disputes. It also provides for the establishment of an investment
promotion center, which should provide all necessary information
to investors.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland's labor and business are generally supportive of the
bill, but are unsure whether it will improve the country's
ability to compete in the region.
</P>
<P>
It was not enough to drop corporate tax rates when many
Southern African countries already had lower tax rates, Swaziland
Chamber of Commerce and Industry Executive Dirctor Harvey Bird
said.
</P>
<P>
"We must demonstrate that we are facilitating new investment
in the kingdom," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland, bordering with South Africa and Mozambique, is a
landlocked country with its economy having been improved
remarkably in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
