<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa today called on
those involved in fighting in the Congo capital of Brazzaville to
agree to ceasefire with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the South African Department of Foreign
Affairs appealed the warring sides to engage in discussion to
bring about a peaceful and lasting solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Fighting evloved into anarchy and a full-scale battle for
control of the capital, witnesses said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Congolese nationals streaming across the river to Kingshasa,
Zaire said Sassou-Nguesso's millitia had fought its way to the
center of the capital and captured televison and radio stations.
</P>
<P>
Fighting broke out in Brazzaville on June 5 after government
forces attempted to disarm members of a 5,000 private militia
loyal to former leader Denis Sassou-Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
At least one French soldier and two government soldiers have
died in the violence, according to informed sources reaching
here. Besides, a number of South Africans, including some
businessmen, were reportedly rapped in Brazzaville due to the
ongoing fighting.
</P>
<P>
Congo President Pascal Lissouba won multiparty elections in
1992, thus ending Sassou-Nguesso's 13-year one-party rule.
</P>
<P>
Congo gained independecne from France in 1960 and has been
plagued by sporadic political and ethnic unrest since the early
1970s. 
