<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries today.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The World Bank has offered Jordan 100 million
U.S. dollars in loans for its energy and social security sectors,
Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister for Development
Prime Ministry Affairs Jawad Anani, 40 million dollars of the
fund will be allocated to help restructure Jordan's energy sector
and the remaining 60 million dollars will be earmarked for a
planned social security net program designed to deal with
unemployment and poverty issues of the country.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has so far lent about 1.4 billion dollars to
Jordan since the early 1960s, and all but 250 million dollars of
the amount had been disbursed by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The World Bank (WB) will provide Lebanon 1.6 billion
U.S. dollars during next four years as a sign of faith in the
country's reconstruction, the local newspaper Daily Star reported
today.
</P>
<P>
That means the WB will increase its annual financial package
to 400 million dollars from the present level of 100 million, the
World Bank Governor James Wolfenson told a press conference he
held jointly with Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
Other than the 400-million-dollar annual basket allotted to
Lebanon, Wolfenson said, Lebanon will also get 600 million
dollars over the next four years from the International Finance
Corporation (IFC), an offshoot of the bank.
</P>
<P>
Wolfenson maintained that Lebanon's financial package is
higher than that of other countries in the region, and stressed
that the world financial body has allocated a total of 604
million dollars in loans to Lebanon since March 1993.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Water Commissioner Meir Ben-Meir and his
Jordanian counterpart have agreed that Israel will soon begin
drilling for water in the Jordanian sector of the Arava, reported
The Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
The move is in line with the peace pact signed between the two
neighbors in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Technical and licensing details, along with the exact
locations, will be agreed upon later this month.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The U.S.-based drugs giant, Merck, has established
a new subsidiary in Israel for the marketing of its medications
and conducting research, according to a report by The Jerusalem
Post today.
</P>
<P>
Merck, which will continue to use the Israeli company Teva
for the production and distribution of its drugs in Israel, has
been selling here since 1953 through Assia-Reisl, a Teva
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
The parent company decided to upgrade its dealings with
Israel, because of the very high level of medicine and government
support for direct involvement by international firms in Israel,
according to its chairman and chief executive officer Raymond
Gilmartine.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Communication Minister Limor Livnat is
leaving the country today on an official visit to Vietnam and the
Philippines for bilateral cooperation in the fields of high-tech
and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The pro-government newspaper The Jerusalem Post reported,
accompanied by leaders of a number of high-tech companies, Livnat
will meet with her counterpart in Vietnam and various political
leaders.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, she will confer with a number of
ministers and telecommunications officials. She will also sign
a cooperation agreement in telecommunications and postal services
between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
