<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Insists on Democracy in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Officials of the Nigerian government
insisted on Sunday night that the coup soldiers in Sierra Leone
would be dislodged from power "by other means" if negotiations
failed, the "Guardian" reported today.
</P>
<P>
"If they don't yield to logic, we will take other measures,"
the national daily quoted an authoritative source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made in the wake of a faltering diplomatic
initiative by rebel soldiers in Sierra Leone to win foreign
sympathy for the ouster of democratically elected government led
by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The coup leaders dispatched emissaries at the weekend to Cote
d'Ivoire and Burkina Faso, among others, apparently to solicit
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
On whether the government has a time frame for its initiative,
the source explained: "We are talking to other people and trying
to get some other things done. So, you cannot set a deadline
yet."
</P>
<P>
According to him, the rebels are talking to some mediators,
among whom are believed to be Ivorians.
</P>
<P>
"There is hardly any face-to-face contact now between Nigeria
and the rebels. Very soon, there has to be a face-to-face
contact," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, observers here noted the temporary respite may have
given room for burgeoning confidence in the Sierra Leonean coup
makers as the coup leader, Major Johnny Koroma on Sunday made his
first public outing in Freetown, capital of the tiny west African
country.
</P>
<P>
Government officials in Abuja, Nigeria, acknowledged that the
ECOMOG venture to remove the coup leaders may be somewhat tricky.
</P>
<P>
"It might be difficult, it may not be as easy as some people
think," said one source, quoted by the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, as a sign of burgeoning confidence in the besieged
coup soldiers, the new military regime announced on Sunday that
it had reopened the country's borders, which were closed shortly
after the coup on May 25. 
</P>
