<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1200 GMT, June 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- The hijack of an Air Malta plane ended peacefully at
the Cologne-Bonn international airport with the surrender of the
two hijackers this morning, said reports reaching here. The two
hijackers emerged out of the Boeing 737 jetliner with hands up
after giving up their weapons to the air crew, police said.
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Higher payments recently introduced by the Kenyan
government for all Internet services providers may reduce the
number of users and force smaller operators out of the market, the
"East African" reported today. All Internet services providers in
the country will pay a five-year leasing fee of 8,200 U.S. dollars
from now to the government for connection to the high-speed
64-kilobyte international line.
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- Visiting Chinese leader Li Ruihuan met with Berlin
Mayor Eberhard Diepgen here, both expressing the hope that
friendly relations and cooperation between the two sides will be
further strengthened. Li, chairman of the National Committee of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC),
said Berlin has played an important role in the development of the
friendly relations between China and Germany.
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga today
reshuffled her cabinet. Changes have been made to several
ministers, according to official sources here.
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Asia Oil and Gas Conference 1997 opened here
today to deliberate on pressing issues in the energy industry. The
two-day conference will discuss questions such as global energy
perspectives and outlook, regional economics and politics,
cooperation and investment opportunities in Asia, and new business
strategies.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran voiced its concern over the presence by Turkish
military forces in northern Iraq, saying it is "sensitive" to
Iraqi territorial integrity. Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister
Alaeddin Bourujerdi told reporters Sunday that Iran gave
importance to the security of regional states and understood the
Turkish security problems.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Ireland's opposition alliance, including Fianna Fail
and Progressive Democrats, has won a narrow victory in the
country's general election by snatching 81 of the 166 seats in the
lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait expressed the hope that its relations
with France will remain solid under a new French government. While
congratulating the election of Lionel Jospin as the new French
prime minister, Kuwaiti Minister of Cabinet Affairs Abdul Aziz
Dehkil Al-Dekhil said that Kuwait highlighted Paris "support to
Kuwait's just causes." 
</P>
