<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Studies Antibiotic Therapy against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- South Afrcian medical
researchers are studying antibiotic therapy against heart attacks
and strokes, local daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
A clinical trial involving 25 patients with various vascular
diseases triggered by atherosclerosis, commonly known as
hardening of the arteries and a major cause of heart and brain
attacks, has begun at Johannesburg Ceneral Hospital.
</P>
<P>
The patients, whose ages range from 40 to 70, are being given
the antibiotic, azithromycin in a six-month experiment involving
the early use of antibiotics to help avert heart attacks and
strokes possibly cuased by a little-known germ, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The researchers include a senior pathologist from the National
Occupational Health Center Dr. Allan Shor, who in 1990 discovered
the first evidence of infected cells in the tissue of diseased
arteries.
</P>
<P>
Shor's find of arterial infection was a major breakthrough
after five years of research in Europe and the United States in
the germ, Chlamydia Pneumoniae, and the presence of its
antibodies in the blood of patients with coronary artery disease.
</P>
<P>
The germ is spread by coughing and sneezing and initially
attacks in the respiratory system, sometimes leading to
pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
Subsequent experiments in Finland, Italy, Britain, Canada and
the U.S. confirmed that the germ might be the cause of diseases
other than respiratory ailments.
</P>
<P>
Once the results of the first batch of volunteers are known,
Shor plans to test 75 more subjects with serious peripheral
vascular disease and cerebrovascular and cardiac diseases, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Urban Residents Report Bigger Income Growth in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey shows that
residents of Chinese cities have seen speedier growth in their
annual income over the past years.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by the State Statistics Bureau among
40,000 families from the country's cities, where 87.4 million
families live.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, urban families with an annual income
surpassing 10,000 yuan (about 1,204 U.S. dollars) totaled 66.42
million in 1996, accounting for 76 percent of the families
surveyed, a rise of 70 percentage points over 1991
record. Meanwhile, the number of urban families with annual income
standing at from 30,000 yuan to 100,000 yuan was also increasing.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there were 1.92 million families with yearly earnings
above 100,000 yuan; 6.25 million families with annual income
between 30,000 yuan to 100,000 yuan; 58.29 million families with
income between 10,000 yuan to 30,000 yuan; 19.26 million families
with an income ranging from 5,000 yuan to 10,000 yuan; and 1.68
million families lived on an annual income below 5,000 yuan,
according to sources.
</P>
<P>
Incomes in different areas varies widely, with those in coastal
cities much higher and those of inland cities significantly lower.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-five percent of the families with income exceeding
100,000 yuan were from south China's Guangdong Province, totalling
1.06 million households, as well as 180,000 families in Shanghai,
120,000 in Zhejiang Province and 100,000 in Jiangsu Province, with
Shanxi, Jilin, Jiangxi, Guizhou, Qinghai and Ningxia having a very
small proportion of families earning this level of income.
</P>
<P>
Families with an annual income of 10,000 yuan to 30,000 yuan
were equally distributed throughout the country, the survey
revealed.
</P>
<P>
China had 3.063 million poor families and 11.76 million
residents in its urban areas in 1996, representing a reduction of
266,000 families and 660,000 residents respectively from the
previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
