<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Call for Remembrance of Historical Humiliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Some 20 days before the return of
Hong Kong, Chinese scholars have urged their countrymen to
remember the great humiliation they suffered a hundred years ago.
</P>
<P>
On June 9, 1898, Britain forced the Chinese government to sign
"The Convention Respecting An Extension of The Hong Kong
Territory," under which the New Territories were leased to Britain
for 99 years.
</P>
<P>
A group of historians from the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences today referred to it as "The Day of National Humiliation."
</P>
<P>
At a meeting marking the 99th anniversary of the event, Liu
Yongsu, an expert on the history of Hong Kong, said that the loss
of Hong Kong resulted from the invasion of British warships. It
also could be attributed to China's weak national strength and the
corrupt, ineffectual government of the Qing Dynasty, he said.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the convention indicates that "if a country lags
behind the rest of the world, it cannot avoid being trampled
upon," he said.
</P>
<P>
Liu added that in the years since Hong Kong was seized, the
British government has cruelly oppressed the territory and is
responsible for racial discrimination there.
</P>
<P>
Xu Yuebiao, another expert on the history of Hong Kong, said
that the Sino-British negotiation concerning the Hong Kong issue
in the 1980s has become an important topic of academic discussion
among historians.
</P>
<P>
"The nature of the Hong Kong issue is clear," he said. "It
derived from the British policy of invading China and the unequal
treaties China was forced to sign with Britain last century."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Shunhong, a research fellow, said that the Hong Kong
handover symbolizes a transition in international relations from
unequal to equal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
