<HEADLINE> Putonghua Courses Popular in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of Hong Kong
people are queuing up to sign on for Putonghua courses as the
handover approaches.
</P>
<P>
Employers are stepping up their Putonghua training programs to
ensure staff, including senior business executives, civil
servants, teachers and salespeople, are bilingual or trilingual.
</P>
<P>
Today's South China Morning Post reported that the territory's
biggest employer, the Hong Kong Government, has taken 19,800
people through their northern tones since 1992, seeing a sevenfold
increase in student numbers in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Civil Service Training and Development Institute chief training
officer Patrick Wong said some 300 Putonghua courses were
scheduled for 7,300 civil servants in the 1997-98 year.
</P>
<P>
The number of civil servants taking the language courses had
jumped from 1,000 in 1992-93 to 7,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce has also organized
more than 10 introductory Putonghua courses for its English
speaking members.
</P>
<P>
"The response was very good," a spokesman said. "Students
included directors, managers and other senior executives who are
keen to learn the language to deal with their counterparts in
China."
</P>
<P>
Learning Putonghua is also becoming mandatory at universities.
From this academic year, the Hong Kong Chinese University requires
all newly admitted students to take a Putonghua course. It is the
first institute to make the language compulsory.  
</P>
</TEXT>
