<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Visiting Japanese Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that Sino-Japanese relations can have a healthy, steady and
lasting development so long as the two sides abide by principles
set forth in the joint statement and the treaty of peace and
friendship, and handle the development direction of bilateral ties
from a long-term and strategic perspective.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remark while meeting with visiting Japanese
Minister of International trade and industry Shinji Sato.
</P>
<P>
Noting that this year is the 25th anniversary of the
normalization of Sino-Japanese diplomatic relations, Li said that
it is an important year in the history of bilateral relations, and
worth commemorating.
</P>
<P>
He said that bilateral economic and trade relations enjoy an
important position in China's foreign economic and trade
relations, adding that the two countries have a long history of
bilateral economic and trade exchanges, Japan is China's biggest
trade partner, and there is a vast potential for furthering
bilateral economic and trade ties.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that both sides raise bilateral economic
and trade cooperation to a new level under the principle of
equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Li said he is expecting Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto's scheduled visit to China, hoping that the visit can
play an important role in promoting bilateral good-neighborly
friendship.
</P>
<P>
Li also briefed Sato on China's economic situation in the first
half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Sato said that China's economic development and vigorous
diplomacy have left a deep impression on him, adding that Hong
Kong's coming return should be congratulated and celebrated.
</P>
<P>
In the past 25 years, Sato noted, Japan-China trade volume has
increased rapidly, and he hopes to further expand bilateral
cooperation in various fields including energy in the years to
come.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government will actively support its
non-governmental enterprises to conduct industrial cooperation
with China, Sato said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Hashimoto's scheduled visit to China later
this year and Li's scheduled visit to Japan within the year will
have an important influence on the development of bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Japanese government has always supported
China's early entry into the World Trade Organization, holding
that this issue should not be politicalized.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Wu
Yi, Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, and Japanese
Ambassador to China Yoshiyasu Sato attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
