<HEADLINE> Malta Plane Hijack Ends Peacefully in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The hijack of an Air Malta plane ended
peacefully at the Cologne-Bonn international airport in the
surrender of the two hijackers this morning, a few hours after the
incident began, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The two hijackers emerged out of the Boeing 737 jetliner with
hands up after giving up their weapons to the air crew, police said.
</P>
<P>
Police said 79 passengers and six crew were on the flight
scheduled to Istanbul from Valletta, Malta. Five hostages were
freed about an hour after the plane landed at the Cologne-Bonn
airport, including a woman who was taken to hospital for her heart
condition.
</P>
<P>
The jet landed on 4:48 a.m. local time in Germany. The
hijackers asked for a television crew to board the plane to record
a message for broadcasting, which demanded the release of Ali
Agca, who is serving a life sentence in an Italian prison for
trying to assassinate Pope John Paul II in 1981.
</P>
<P>
The hijackers seized the flight after it took off and forced it
to land at the Cologne-Bonn airport. The hijacked plane was taxied
to a cargo area of the Cologne-Bonn airport, with normal
operations at the airport continuing a few hundreds yards away
throughout the incident.
</P>
<P>
Police took a low-key approach in dealing with the incident and
used a Turkish speaking translator during the negotiations with
the hijackers, said the reports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
