</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Religions in China (7) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In drafting laws and regulations on religion, the Chinese
government has taken the heed to reflect the policy of freedom of
religious belief and has repeatedly solicited opinions from
various aspects of the society, especially religious groups. The
laws and regulations have therefore won approval and support from
religious believers and are understood and respected by an
increasing number of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The Religious Affairs Bureau of the State Council and religious
departments at various government levels take charge of handling
religious affairs in China. They are entrusted with the
responsibility of impementing the laws, reguations and poilicies
regarding religious affairs, as well as supervising them.
</P>
<P>
The responsibilities of these departments includes implementing
the policy of freedom of religious belief in accordance with the
Constitution and law and coordinating the relationship between
religious groups and other parts of society. It is also their duty
to protect the religious belief of citizens, and the rights and
interests of religious groups, churches, and monasteries, and
handling religious affairs in accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
The government departments must exercise their administrative power
in accordance with the law, and shall not infringe upon religious
freedom of citizens and the legitimate rights and interests of
religious organizations and places of worship.
</P>
<P>
The government has dealt with in time misconduct that goes
against the policy of freedom of religious belief. Article 251
(formerly Article 147) of the Criminal Law of the People's Repulic
of China explicitly states that "serious cases in which any
government employee illegally deprives citizens of their rights to
religious belief and infringes upon ethnic customs and practices,
may result in custody or a sentence of two years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Religions in China (8) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In China, religious leaders hold seats in the People's Congress
and the People's Political Consultative Conference at different
levels and take part in government and political affairs and
discussions.
</P>
<P>
More than 17,000 religious authorities have been elected
deputies to the People's Congress and the People's Political
Consultative Conference at different levels in various parts of
China. Pagbalha Geleg Namgyai, a living Buddha and vice-president
of the Chinese Buddhist Association and honorary president of its
Tibetan branch, was elected vice-chairman of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Puchu, president of the Chinese Buddist Association, and
Ding Guangxun, honorary president of the China Christian Council,
have held the positions of vice-chairman of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference, and therefore become state
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Religious leaders who are deputies to the People's Congress or
members of the People's Political Consultative Conference at
different levels have taken part in discussions of state affairs
in the same manner as those non-religious counterparts do.
</P>
<P>
They also oversee the implementing of religious policies and
make suggestions, thereby enjoying equally democratic rights in
political life.
</P>
<P>
In today's world, ethnic disputes and religious conflicts have
occured repeatedly elsewhere, but a stable and harmonious
religious atmosphere has been maintained in China.
</P>
<P>
In the country, different ethnic groups, various religious
organizations and people of religion or non-religion, respect one
another and live in harmony, working together for the prosperity
of the motherland. China is now a country that enjoys political stability,
economic prosperity, ethnic unity, and social tranquility.
</P>
<P>
This fully demonstrates that the Chinese government has
implemented a policy of freedom of religious belief, and that it
has successfully managed religious affairs. And it will continue
its efforts in this respect.
</P>
</TEXT>
