<HEADLINE> World's 1st Nationwide Multimedia Broadband Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The world's first nationwide
high-bandwidth communication network, called Singapore ONE, was
launched here today by Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong as
he opened the Asia Telecom 97, the largest telecommunication show
in the Asia Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
He said more than 400 households will participate in the
Singapore ONE pilot project and the number will increase to more
than 5,000 households before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, namely within 18 months, all 800,000
households in Singapore will be able to connect to Singapore ONE,
while businesses, schools and public areas will also be networked,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The pilot network and some of the services of Singapore ONE
include tele-shopping, digital library, educational services,
training and entertainment services, at speeds more than a hundred
times faster, and of higher quality, than what is currently
available over the Internet, he said.
</P>
<P>
Singapore ONE, a national information infrastructure that will
handle a wide ranging stream of multimedia traffic, such as voice,
data, image text and video, to the workplace, the homes and
schools, was initiated a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"Singapore ONE will transform Singapore into an Intelligent
Island, a place where information technology enhances our quality
of living, at work, at home and at play," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Religions in China (9) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
III. Remarkable Achievements Made by China's Religious
Communities in the Field of Foreign Exchanges
</P>
<P>
Religious organizations in China have established friendly ties
with religious groups and personages in more than 70 countries and
regions all over the world. Since the beginning of the 1980s, the
organizations have enhanced international contacts and exchanges
and the major international exchanges have increased. This has
promoted mutual understanding and friendship and helped to
maintain world peace.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Thailand's Sangharaja, the religious leader of Thai
Buddhists, visited China and met President Jiang Zemin; in 1994,
the fingers of a Buddha found in China were sent to Thailand to be
enshrined and worshipped for 85 days; at the invitation of the
Christian Council of China, two archbishops of Canterbury paid
friendly visits to China successively; in 1995 and in 1996,
conferences were held in Beijing and the Republic of Korea (ROK)
respectively, for friendly exchanges among Buddhists in China, the
ROK and Japan; in 1994 and 1996, the Buddha's teeth were sent to
Myanmar to be enshrined at the invitation of the Myanmese
government.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, more than 40,000 Chinese Muslims have made
pilgrimages to Mecca.
</P>
<P>
Chinese religious organizations and personages have also joined
some international religious organizations and participated in
international conferences on religion.
</P>
</TEXT>
