<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Religions in China (10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Buddhist Association of China (BAC) is a member of the
World Fellowship of Buddhists. Its chairman, Zhao Puchu, is a vice
chairman of the organization.
</P>
<P>
The Christian Council of China (CCC) formally joined the World
Council of Churches in 1992; its honorary chairman Ding Guangxun
is a vice chairman of the organization.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Chinese Catholics were present at a world
conference for Catholic youth, and Chinese Taoists went to Japan
and Britain for world conferences on religion and environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
The freedom of religious belief of foreign nationals is
respected and protected in China: they can attend religious
activities in Chinese temples, mosques and churches open to them.
</P>
<P>
At the request of the Chinese organizing committee of the
Fourth World Conference on Women in 1995, religious groups in
Beijing provided religious services for representatives to the
conference, with temporary sites for religious activities set up
at the main venue in the Asian Games Village and the NGO Forum
venue in Huairou.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, the religious groups and sites in
Beijing received more than 10,000 representatives from 103
countries and regions, including Gertrude Mongella,
secretary-general of the conference, former Tanzanian president
Julius Nyerere, the first lady of Djibuti, Italian and South
African government ministers, former US president George Bush, a
French bishop and officials in charge of women's affairs in world
religious organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
