<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Religions in China (11) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After attending religious services in a local church during a
visit to Xi'an in 1996, the German president and the first lady
expressed their deep satisfaction with the church. In March 1997,
Australian Prime Minister John Howard and Newt Gingrich, speaker
of the US House of Representatives, and his wife, went to the
Community Church in Shanghai for the Easter service, along with
their entourage of 70. They were impressed with the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
According to a radio program broadcasted in "the Voice of
America" on March 31, Gingrich was very pleased with the service,
and said that his visit to the church had strengthened his
confidence that the US should increase contacts and develop
relations with China.
</P>
<P>
When Prime Minister Howard left the church, he shook the
pastor's hand and said that the service was very good, and had
moved him deeply.
</P>
<P>
When Richard Rigby, Australian Consul General in Shanghai came to
the church to express appreciation on behalf of Prime Minister
Howard, he said it couldn't be said that there was no problem with
the issue of religious belief in China now, but it was not as bad
as some people made it out to be, most of whom did not understand
China's conditions.
</P>
<P>
China's gate is always open to foreigners who are friendly with
China, who abide by China's laws and respect Chinese religious
organizations, regardless of which country they come from or which
religions they believe in.
</P>
