<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Religions in China (12) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VI. To claim that China practices "persecution of religious
people" and "intolerance of religion" is slanderous and has
ulterior motives.
</P>
<P>
China's policy of freedom of religious belief has been
supported and welcomed by the religious people in the country, and
has been praised by some people in the international community.
</P>
<P>
But in recent years, some Westerners have turned a blind eye to
the fact that there are hundreds of millions of religious people
and thousands of religious organizations in China which are
engaging in a large number of normal religious activities.
</P>
<P>
They called with ulterior motives the Chinese government's
crackdown on the activities of a small number of cults, which
threatened the social and public interests, "persecution of
religious people" and "intolerance of religion".
</P>
<P>
In truth, since the 1980s, a group of cults have formed in some
places around China. Some have spread to China from abroad and
some have grown and developed on Chinese soil.
</P>
<P>
These quasi-religious organizations, though small in number,
have greatly harmed Chinese society.
</P>
<P>
The heads and core members of these organizations are people
who did not live by honest labor, preferring to enjoy an easy life
and hating to work.
</P>
<P>
They distorted the religious doctrines, spread heresy, incited
people to violate the nation's laws and intended to overthrow the
government.
</P>
<P>
They cheated people with superstitious beliefs, purposely
created to enshroud simple ideas in mystery, and hurt and injured
people, some of whom were handicapped or even died.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they assembled groups to participate in
promiscuous activities, raped women, swindled people out of their
money, and seriously disturbed people's daily life.
</P>
<P>
Both ordinary people and the religious people detested these
practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Religion in China (13) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Consider Wu Yangming, who founded the "the Established King
Sect" in east China's Anhui Province. Wu spread heresy, and
claimed that his group will "unite the country in the spirit of
the "the Established King Sect".
</P>
<P>
He said that they will build "a magic country with a new heaven
and earth," and demanded the women believers "not only worship his
soul but also his body." Wu, in collusion with other key members
of the organization, have seduced and raped 19 young women, the
youngest of whom is only 14 years old.
</P>
<P>
The sentence of Wu and his partners by the Chinese judicial
departments drew applause and the deep gratitude of the local
people.
</P>
<P>
Another example is Xu Yongze in central China's Henan Province,
who has been made well-known by some of the American media in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Xu was the head of the cult "the Wholistic Sect", which was
founded in the province in 1984. He flagrantly spread among the
ordinary people the idea that the "end of the world will come
soon," and that "people can only be reborn and save themselves by
crying out."
</P>
<P>
Under his influence, many people quit their jobs and gathered
together to cry and shout, which resulted in many cases of mental
disturbance.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Xu has intensified his illegal activities and
adversely affected the normal production and daily life of people
in a number of areas.
</P>
<P>
The local department of public security detained him in
accordance with the law, after it obtained a large amount of
evidence concerning his activities.
</P>
<P>
Some people in the United States began to pass around the rumor
that "Xu was already sentenced to death", and even asked for
"trade sanctions" against China when the case was still in the
trial basis.
</P>
<P>
The "evidence" they referred to are simply China's crackdown on
the cults, and its punishment for disturbances of the social
order, rape, hooliganism, swindling and other crimes committed in
name of religion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
