<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cause of Assassination on Kuwaiti MP Revealed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti English Daily Arab
Times said today that the assassination attempt on a Kuwaiti
member of parliament (MP) was aimed at stopping impeachment of
government officials.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Al-Jarallah, editor-in-chief of the paper, said in a
front page story that informed sources revealed the failed
attempt on Abdullah Al-Neibari, a liberal MP, was "purely local in
nature and believed to be a form of settling of old and new scores
among different groups."
</P>
<P>
The 61-year-old outspoken MP and his wife were shot and wounded
by gunmen as they drove back from their seaside villa
in the southern part of Kuwait Friday.
</P>
<P>
Neibari is renowned for his fiery speeches on the floor of
the chamber against corruption and embezzlement of public funds.
</P>
<P>
Three Kuwaitis and two Iranians were arrested on charge of the
attack 24 hours later and referred to public prosecution for
interrogations.
</P>
<P>
Al-Jarallah stressed that the sources who have been closely
following the events and investigations revealed that names of
high ranking officials were mentioned during the interrogations.
</P>
<P>
Initial investigations showed that a number of parliamentary
members were preparing to grill a number of cabinet ministers and
the gunmen carried out the assassination attempt to stop such a
move, Al-Jarallah said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the assassination attempt on Neibari "will
most likely lead to fundamental changes in the government and may
result in the dissolution of the National Assembly."
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Acting Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh
Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah Saturday called on security authorities
to foil schemes by perpetrators who wanted to incite discords in
the country by attempting to kill a parliamentary member.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the whole country to stay calm and refrain
from inciting further tension.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti cabinet Sunday met to discuss the criminal incident
and praised the Interior Ministry for the speedy apprehension of
the suspects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several Issues on Religion in China (14) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In China, people who do not believe in any religion as well as
those who do have the same rights and obligations under the law
and no one is granted special privileges.
</P>
<P>
Anyone who commits a crime will be held criminally responsible,
whether or not the person believes in a particular religion.
</P>
<P>
No one will be detained or put into prison for following a
religion or engaging in normal religious activities. But a handful
of people who have refused to obey the law and were involved in
illegal activities in the name of religion should be punished in
accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
No country in the world allows illegal behavior and crime in
the name of religion.
</P>
<P>
Just a few years ago, The United States took extreme measures,
including using helicopters, tanks and armored cars, against the
Branch Davidian cult in Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
Japan also took severe measures to settle the case of the
poisonous gas attack in a Tokyo subway on March 20, 1995,
committed by the Aum Shinrikyo religious cult.
</P>
<P>
The religious cults and their actions, which proved dangerous
to society and the public welfare, were punished to safeguard the
people and the sanctity of the law and to maintain social order.
</P>
<P>
Such punishment was also done on behalf of the citizens'
freedom of religious belief and to ensure that normal religious
activities continue.
</P>
<P>
It is groundless and creates suspicion when some people attack
China's crackdown on criminals by saying that it instead
"persecutes religious people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0120 </DOCNO>
