Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Three weeks after the fall of Kinshasa, Brazzaville, which is
a stone's throw across the Congo River, has flared up.
</P>
<P>
Government troops and the militiamen supporting former President
Denis Sassou Nguesso have been fighting since Thursday in the
capital of Congo Republic. French officials stationed in Brazzaville
said that the militiamen of Sassou Nguesso seemed to be gaining the
upper hand while the government troops are losing ground.
</P>
<P>
-- After the beginning of democratic alternative in Congo
Republic in August 1992, when Pascal Lissouba replaced Sassou
Nguesso as president, the national conscience of the country has
ceased to exist, its government is ravaged by corruption, and
its regular army has run out of money, equipments and qualified
soldiers. Moreover, the ``oil war'' between French and American oil
companies has worsened the conflict in the country.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- During his visit in Lille in northern France last weekend,
President Jacques Chirac reaffirmed the ``fundamental role of the
president of the republic as the guardian of government
institutions'' during the period of cohabitation between the right
and the left. He also stressed the need for the two poles of the
executive administration -- the presidence and the government -- to
``serve together the interests'' of France.
</P>
<P>
-- French Prime Miniser Lionel Jospin said on Sunday that
France will do what it necessary to guarantee the security of
French nationals in Brazzaville, capital of the Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
Five hundred French soldiers will arrive in Brazzaville today to
reinforce the 450 French troops already stationed there. A Transall
transport aircraft of the French army landed in the Congolese
capital Sunday evening. 
