<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 08:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnia Awaits Turkey's Financial Aid: Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A senior Bosnian diplomat has
called on Turkey to fulfill its promise to grant financial aid
to help rebuild the war-stricken country.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Ambassador to Ankara, Hajrudin Somun, made the remarks
in an exclusive interview with local newspaper Daily News, which
was published today.
</P>
<P>
Somun said that Turkey, in accordance with the protocol
signed at the International Donors Conference in 1996, should
give Bosnia-Herzegovina 80 million U.S. dollars of credits and
grants, but only 2.2 million dollars has been supplied to date.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's failure to fulfill its financial promise has
been creating certain "misunderstandings," the ambassador said,
adding that this issue would be discussed during the visit of
Bosnian head of state to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Alija Izetbegovic, president of Bosnia-Herzegovina, arrived
here Sunday night and will begin his official visit to Turkey
today.
</P>
<P>
Somun said: "I hope it (the aid to Bosnia) is part of the
budget in Turkey this year." He admitted, however, that he was
not optimistic about this.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bosnian ambassador stressed that money was
especially important for his country, which has no economic
growth as a result of the destruction a protracted civil war.
</P>
<P>
Despite the complaints about the delays, Somun also
maintained that his country thanked Turkey for its support in
various fields, saying that the Bosnian-Turkish relations were
good.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here noted that the remarks made by the
Bosnian ambassador aimed to remind Ankara of its obligations
provided by the International Donors Conference, whose annual
meeting falls on June 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
