<HEADLINE> Election Hopefuls Urged to Resign in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi has
directed civil servants who intend to stand in the coming general
elections to resign and start seeking votes.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper "Daily Nation" today said that Moi's
direction is a further indication that the polls "cannot be far
off".
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the president as saying yesterday in Kiambu
District that the constitution is too important to be changed in
a brief period as the time left before the polls.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of opposition parties, churches and NGOs have
persisted in "minimum constitutional reforms" before the general
elections and threatened to storm Kenyan parliament on June 19 to
derail the national budget speech and force the government to
effect constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
Moi said that he has a constitutional duty to maintain
security and dares the opposition to cause any form of
lawlessness in the country as they threatened.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Ford-Kenya Chairman Kijana Wamalwa said on Sunday
that opposition leaders had failed to agree on a single
presidential candidate in the coming poll.
</P>
<P>
He asked President Moi to delay the elections to enable
constitutional review to take place and challenged the government
to organize a national convention to get the views of the people
on the issue. 
</P>
