<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firearms, Knives Create Crisis in S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Violence and murder have
often occurred in schools in Soweto, a black township near
Johannesburg of South Africa when pupils come to class with
knives and guns, local daily "The Star" reported today.
</P>
<P>
There are many stabbing or shooting incidents in or near
school premises involving pupils, the report quoted Wandile
Zwane, a spokesman for the Center for the Study of Violence and
Rehabilitation as saying.
</P>
<P>
Zwane attributed the increasing violence in schools to easy
access to firearms in townships. "There is also no culture of
learning, so pupils get involved in other activities," he said.
</P>
<P>
There is no accurate statistics on the number of violent
crimes taking place in schools. But Soweto's police said bloody
incidents are reported almost every month, noting most cases go
unreported.
</P>
<P>
Zwane said Soweto teachers feel powerless to control weapons
in schools for fear of taking risk of their lives.
</P>
<P>
Aubrey Matshiqi, spokesman for Gauteng Provincial Education
Department, which is responsible for Soweto schools, said his
department was consulting teachers' unions and many suggestions
had been made, including the introduction of screening bars or
security guards at schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
