<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Prime Minister to Form New Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- There would be no
constitutional crisis in Lesotho after formation of a new
political party by Prime Minister Ntsu Mokhehle on Saturday,
Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) leader Monyane Moleleki has
said.
</P>
<P>
Moleleki explained yesterday that "we have a different system
of parliament here in Lesotho."
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians are not elected by the party but by
constituencies, he said, adding therefore life will be as normal
when parliament starts tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here today from Maseru, capital
of Lesotho, the LCD is to be launched today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement by the prime minister on the formation of the
new party has sent shock waves in Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
Political observers expressed concern over what impact the
move would have on the country's constitutional process.
</P>
<P>
Moleleki said all members of the new party had resigned with
immediate effect from the Basutoland Congress Party. Their
position would not be affected as a result of their change of
allegiance.
</P>
<P>
According to the new rule, he said, national assembly members
are not delegates of parties, but they are individual
constituencies, which do not have any political coloring.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Mokhehle in April announced his retirement from
politics next year, citing ill-health and old-age as the reasons
for quitting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
