<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lankan Government Forces Advance Slowly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan government troops
engaged in the "Jaya Sikuru" (Certain Victory) military operation
are advancing slowly due to stiff resistance from rebels of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
How fierce the resistance is can be gauged by the fact that
over the weekend the troops were able to advance merely one
kilometer in their effort to recapture 75 kilometers of road on
the main north-south highway which runs through rebel-held
territory in North Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
To gain control of that one kilometer, the government forces
had six troops killed and 21 others injured while the rebels lost
more than 70 cadres.
</P>
<P>
Since the operation was launched on May 13, the forces have
managed to recapture only 16 kilometers of the highway including
the one kilometer over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Recently 130 mm artillery guns were rushed to the battlefield
by the government forces and strength was withdrawn from most
police stations to be reassigned to the war, according to military
sources.
</P>
<P>
Reinforcements were also hurriedly raised from bigger military
installations and sent into the war, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The operation had been temporarily suspended for nine days to
consolidate new positions before they were started again last
Friday by the troops who launched a two-pronged attack on the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Army's 55th Division began its advance along the A9,
Vavuniya-Jaffna Highway from the earlier captured Omantai while
the 53rd Division was pressing ahead from Nedunkerni, also
recaptured in the first stage of the operation, in the direction
of Puliyankulam Town.
</P>
<P>
The two columns are poised to link up at Puliyankulam -- a move
that would effectively separate the rebel-dominated Mulaitivu
jungles from the Weli Oya sector controlled by the security
forces.
</P>
<P>
The thrust launched last Friday is aimed at preempting the
rebels' attempt to regroup or consolidate their positions.
</P>
<P>
However, military sources said they expect strong resistance
from the rebels but are confident that the linkup of the 55th and
53rd divisions at Puliyankulam Town could be achieved in the
coming week.
</P>
<P>
A fuller appraisal of the remaining stages of the operation
would be made only after the linkup at the town.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, the troops of the 55th Division were five
kilometers and those of the 53rd Division eight kilometers away
from Puliyankulam Town.
</P>
<P>
However, the military believe that the main objective of the
recapture of the whole Vavuniya-Jaffna Highway could be achieved
and the highway could be reopened to traffic in a few months.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels, for their part, are planning to devise a
number of incidents in the Jaffna Peninsula and in Trincomalee
with a view to deflecting the operation against them. According to
intelligence reports, large numbers of LTTE rebels have been
arriving in these areas.
</P>
<P>
However, the rebels suffered a setback last week when a fleet
of rebel craft carrying about 200 cadres was blown up in a huge
explosion, the cause of which is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
During the first stage of the operation from May 13 to 24,
about 200 rebels were killed and 316 injured, according to
official figures. The LTTE, which has been fighting for a separate
Tamil state in the northeast of the country, has also suffered
heavy casualties in the second stage of the operation launched by
the troops on May 25.
</P>
<P>
Casualties of the government forces in the operation have been
unusually high but the military have yet to reveal the total
number of the killed and injured.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
