<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Raises Payments for Internet Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Higher payments recently
introduced by the Kenyan government for all Internet services
providers may reduce the number of users and force smaller
operators out of the market, the "East African" reported today.
</P>
<P>
All Internet services providers in the country will pay a
five-year leasing fee of 8,200 U.S. Dollars from now to the Kenya
Posts and Telecommunication Corporation (KP&AMP;TC) for connection to
the high-speed 64-kilobyte international line, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, all providers will be charged an annual interim
payment of 4,716 Dollars or one percent of their gross turnover.
</P>
<P>
Firms will also be expected to provide a list of all users and
their addresses to the Communications Commission of Kenya, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted industry sources as saying that while most
Internet companies have already complied with the new licensing
conditions, concern is mounting over the smaller companies'
ability to meet the new payment requirement.
</P>
<P>
Multinational services providers have claimed that the
requirement that they hold only up to 70 percent in local
subsidiaries would discourage foreign investment in the sector in
the eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
During an Internet workshop held here last week, participants
complained about the high charges and called for an urgent
meeting between KP&AMP;TC and all Internet service providers to
review them.
</P>
<P>
Fred Bukachi, a senior official at the East African Internet
Association, warned that unless the licensing charges were
revised, Kenya's on-line business would be dominated by foreign
companies.
</P>
<P>
Small non-profitable bodies such as public institutions,
community-based groups and civil organizations interested in
setting up non-commercial Internet services, particularly in the
rural areas, would be discouraged by the charges, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Lucas Kenani, a KP&AMP;TC assistant manager, said the
Internet providers can pass the costs to consumers by adjusting
their prices which are already 10 to 20 percent higher than in
Europe or the United States.
</P>
<P>
The flat monthly fee covering unlimited usage of Internet
services differs from company to company, with the upper limit
being 188 Dollars a month while unlimited E-mail usage costs 47
Dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
The average cost of Internet connection and installation is
about 19 Dollars in Kenya where the Internet computing industry
is estimated to have an annual growth rate of between 50-60
percent with about 5,000 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
The sector is dominated by Africa Online and Form-Net Africa.
Basic services they provide include E-mail, World Wide Web
access, E-mail-to-fax or faxaway and paging and designer products
targeting specific clients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
