<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suzhou Takes Big Steps to Protect Old City (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-seven Suzhou municipal
government departments, which formerly occupied four ancient
courtyards in the world-famous garden city, have been relocated
from the old city area and today opened for business in their new
offices.
</P>
<P>
The relocation is one of the major steps by the municipal
government to reduce the strain of modern-day life on Suzhou,
which has a history of more than 2,500 years.
</P>
<P>
The courtyards that had been used by the government will open
to the public or be used as tourist sites.
</P>
<P>
As part of the city's overall development plan, the move is
designed to cut down noise pollution and better safeguard the
peaceful environment of the gardens, said Zhang Xinsheng, mayor of
Suzhou.
</P>
<P>
So far, the municipal government has moved out 130 factories
and more than 35,000 residents from their former homes. The city
plans to shift another 60,000 people over the next ten years. By
then, one third of the old city-area residents will have been
relocated.
</P>
<P>
"The old city will only appear as the cultural, tourism and
commercial center," Zhang said, adding that by the year of 2000,
Suzhou is to close one third of the present 96 factories in the
old city area, move out another one third and preserve only the
remaining one third that are non-polluters and produce goods
typifying local character, such as embroidery, traditional musical
instruments or stage costumes.
</P>
<P>
For the past decade, Suzhou, which last year had a gross
domestic product of over 100 billion yuan (some 12 billion US
dollars), built all of its new factories in the new city areas.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Weiren, a garden designer, said "the essence of the
Suzhou gardens is their quietness and the reduction of the
population in the old city area is a fairly good plan."
</P>
<P>
The old city was built in 514 B.C. covering 14.2 square
kilometers. It suffered serious damage from wars and uprisings
throughout its history. Rebuilt time and again in the original
site, it has always been the local political and economic center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suzhou Takes Big Steps to Protect Old City (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Surrounded by the city moat, the old city area is crisscrossed
with lanes and waterways and has more than 160 scenic bridges. The
garden designers built more than 100 unique private homes with
courtyards -- now the Suzhou gardens.
</P>
<P>
Yan Daoming, a city planning expert, said "it is necessary to
move the political and industrial centers out of the old city area
to preserve its original beauty."
</P>
<P>
The decision was also supported by I.M Pei, world-renowned
architect and advisor for Suzhou's city construction. "The world
only has one such old city, so it is worthwhile to pay any price
for its protection," Pei said.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yunzhu, a female worker, formerly lived in the old city
area, where it only took her five minutes to walk to her
factory. Four years ago, her chemical plant was moved from the
city center to the new city area, and it takes her 30 minutes
by bike to her plant.
</P>
<P>
Like many other residents of the old city area, she felt
traveling to work was inconvenient.
</P>
<P>
Now, she has moved to her new house in the new city area. She
said, "I chose to move, as I should make an effort to protect the
old city, though I was reluctant to leave the old city area I am
familiar with."
</P>
<P>
Suzhou has spent 30 billion yuan (3.75 billion dollars) in the
past 10 years to build 53 residential villages in western and
eastern parts of the old city, together with department stores,
schools, hospitals, banks and recreational centers.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the city has renovated more than 800 ancient
lanes and 163 bridges. Historic preservation plaques have been
placed on more than 200 ancient buildings and some 500 ancient
trees.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a dredging project has started along the 35-kilometer
ancient river. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
