<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Increase Loans to Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) will provide
Lebanon 1.6 billion U.S. dollars during next four years as a sign
of faith in the country's reconstruction, the local newspaper
Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
That means the WB will increase its annual financial package to
400 million dollars from the present level of 100 million, the
World Bank Governor James Wolfenson told a press conference he
held jointly with Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
Wolfenson, who arrived here from Damascus, Syria, on Sunday
afternoon on his first visit to Lebanon, praised the Lebanese
government for its efforts in rebuilding the war-torn economy and
outlined the financial assistance the bank has planned for
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"My purpose for coming to Lebanon was to look at some of the
work we are doing here. We are a friend and supporter of Lebanon
because we trust the government," he told reporters at the end
of his meeting with Hariri.
</P>
<P>
Other than the 400-million-dollar annual basket allotted to
Lebanon, Wolfenson said, Lebanon will also get 600 million
dollars over the next four years from the International Finance
Corporation (IFC), an offshoot of the bank.
</P>
<P>
"This year alone we have loaned Lebanon so far a total of 170
million dollars and 100 million dollars in guarantees," he said,
noting that additional 150 million dollars were available from
the IFC.
</P>
<P>
He added that there were "no holdbacks or restrictions over
their (funds') use and we are working with the (Lebanese)
government closely."
</P>
<P>
Premier Hariri pointed out that, altogether, Lebanon could
expect 2.2 billion dollars of funds over the next four years from
the WB.
</P>
<P>
Wolfenson maintained that Lebanon's financial package is
higher than that of other countries in the region, and stressed
that the world financial body has allocated a total of 604 million
dollars in loans to Lebanon since March 1993.
</P>
<P>
The additional funds available to Lebanon will reportedly come
amid signs of renewed faith on behalf of the World Bank in the
government's economic policy.
</P>
<P>
In a report published last November, the World Bank praised
the recovery achieved in Lebanon so far and gave an optimistic
prognosis for Lebanon's continued economic performance.
</P>
<P>
The report was issued after Hariri toured some European states
last June to raise 5 billion dollars his government needed to
carry on its ambitious reconstruction plan in the next five
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
