<HEADLINE> Israel Unveils New Unmanned Aerial Vehicle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Elbit System Ltd., one of
Israel's major military firms, is unveiling an advanced
short-range unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) which it says has
garnered interest in Israel and other nations.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Jerusalem Post, the UAV, meant to provide
tactical intelligence for ground forces and direct artillery fire,
is called the Hermes-450S, developed and manufactured by Elbit's
subsidiary Silver Arrow, based in Herzliya near Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The Hermes, a single-engine drone, can stay in the air for 20
hours at an altitude of some 6,100 meters, and except for the
engine, it contains backups of all of its vital systems.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Yeshayahu Shapira, Silver Arrow's managing
director, as saying that there were already several orders for
the Hermes, but he would not identify them.
</P>
<P>
Elbit executives said the Israeli army is likely to order it
as part of its program to update its UAV capability.
</P>
<P>
Elbit has recently won a contract from the Israeli army to
develop advanced avionics for the F-15 upgrade, a contract valued
at 12.5 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The contract will be executed via Elbit's subsidiary EFW,
based in Fort Worth, Texas in the United States.
</P>
<P>
This month, Elbit will supply the first prototypes of the
system to the Israeli Air Force and will install the avionics on
the F-15s in November.
</P>
<P>
Elbit executives also said that they will highlight their
company's ability to upgrade combat jets and helicopters during
next week's Paris Air Show in France.
</P>
<P>
In the air show, Elbit will display the MIG-21 it upgraded for
the Romanian air force, which was executed in accordance with an
agreement between Elbit and Romania to market MIG upgrades to
third countries.
</P>
<P>
Elbit President Joseph Ackerman told the Jerusalem Post that
two-thirds of his company's business stems from upgrades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
