<HEADLINE> Asia Oil &AMP; Gas Conference 1997 Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Asia Oil and Gas Conference
1997 opened here today to deliberate on pressing issues in the
energy industry.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference with the theme "Asia: Preparing for the
Next Millennium" will discuss questions such as global energy
perspectives and outlook, regional economics and politics,
prospects in the Asian upstream sector, cooperation and investment
opportunities in Asia, prospects for futures and derivative
markets and new business strategies.
</P>
<P>
Officiating the conference, Malaysian Acting Prime Minister
Anwar Ibrahim said that driven by rapid economic growth, the
Asia-Pacific region has undergone a vast change over the last
decade and witnessed a significant increase in demand for energy.
</P>
<P>
The region's rapid economic growth creates its own challenges
with one of these coming from the energy sector, he said, warning
that before long, oil production will no longer be adequate to
meet demand.
</P>
<P>
The Asia-Pacific region's current demand for energy is well
over a quarter of the global total and is forecast to rise to
one-third by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
At current rates of production, the region's reserves are
expected to be depleted within 15 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, Asian oil markets will become more dependent on
the Middle East for supplies and under this scenario, natural gas
will play a more prominent role in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
He held that the future of gas is assured with ample reserves
to meet global demand for a long time to come. However, he said
that to ensure future availability of gas, new export projects
will have to be implemented in regions that are far away from
consumer markets.
</P>
<P>
More than 550 participants from 31 countries and regions
including China are attending the conference organized by the
Asian Strategy and Leadership Institute of Malaysia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
