<HEADLINE> Staff Layoffs Likely to Rise in Thailand: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Nearly half of companies in Bangkok
and surrounding areas have laid off, or are considering trimming
their staff because of the economic slump in the country, a recent
local survey said.
</P>
<P>
About 53.9 percent of 1,239 companies surveyed in Bangkok and
its surrounding areas had dismissed or were considering to dismiss
workers, according to the results of the Dusit Poll conducted
between June 1 and 8.
</P>
<P>
Among the companies surveyed, 172, or 13.9 percent of the
total, had already sacked some workers, according to the poll
carried on the local newspaper "The Nation" today.
</P>
<P>
Another 495, or about 40 percent, were considering trimming
their staff.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 231 firms preferred to wait and see how the
economy would fair before they made decisions, while 215 ones
declined to reveal their intentions.
</P>
<P>
Only about seven companies said that they would sack workers,
the poll added.
</P>
<P>
Most of the companies blamed the economic downturn for their
sacking plans, claiming they would choose to lay off those lazy or
inefficient workers if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Some 43 percent of the companies surveyed urged the government
to solve the country's economic problems, while 20 percent called
for a delay of the government's plan to raise the minimum daily
wage around the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
