<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Build World's Tallest Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a 94-storey
skyscraper, believed to be the world's tallest, will start this
September in Cosmopolitan Shanghai and be finished by 2001.
</P>
<P>
The building of the 460-meter Shanghia World Financial Center
will cost 960 million US dollars and will be jointly invested by
Mori Building Co. Ltd, the Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund of
Japan, and 34 other Japanese and US financial companies, said
Youxikawa Kiyouxi with Mori's Forest Overseas Co. Ltd..
</P>
<P>
The office- and hotel-building, located at Lujiazui Financial
and Trade Zone in Shanghai's Pudong New Area, was designed by the US
architectural firm, KPF.
</P>
<P>
Kiyouxi said it was Pudong's promising future of economic
development that encouraged Mori to put up 30 percent of the total
investment into the project.
</P>
<P>
Mori is currently building a 50-storey office tower near the
site of the skyscraper.
</P>
<P>
When built, the Shanghai World Financial Center will be eight
meter's taller than the current record-holder Petronas Twin Towers
in Malaysia's Kuala Lumpur, which is 451.9 meters in height.
</P>
<P>
The 68-storey 384-m-high Diwang (King of the Land) Commercial
Mansion in south China's booming city of Shenzhen is holding the
record of China at present.
</P>
<P>
Some other Chinese big cities, including Guangzhou, Chongqing,
and Beijing, are also planning to erect skyscrapers over 100
stories, according to early reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
