<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 429 Fires Hit U.S. Churches Since 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A total of 429 arsons and
bombings have struck churches across the United States since 1995,
with 38 percent done in black churches, a report by a national
arson organization said today.
</P>
<P>
Although 162 black churches suffered burning attacks between
January 1, 1995 and May 27, 1997, the National Church Arson Task
Force said that black churches were not major targets of criminals
and there have not been enough evidence of "a national conspiracy"
aimed at colored people.
</P>
<P>
The task force, formed by the order of President Bill Clinton a
year ago to coordinate probes into a string of suspected racist
fires in black churches, said that conspiracy charges were filed
in "a limited number of cases" and they "tended to be confined to
a small geographic area."
</P>
<P>
But some pastors disagreed, saying they were racial. "It is
terror perpetrated against people of color who have no defense,"
said the Rev. Robert Jeffrey, pastor of New Hope Baptist Church in
Seattle who is attending a three-day conference in Washington
Sunday on rebuilding the burned churches.
</P>
<P>
The organization said that 110 suspects, 85 percent of which
white, were convicted in 77 fires, or 18 percent of the total
arsons, bombings or attempted bombings.
</P>
<P>
More than three quarters of the attacked black churches are in
the South, it said. The burned churches also include 11 synagogs
and four mosques.
</P>
<P>
Federal and state authorities arrested 199 suspects, 42 percent
of which juveniles, in 150 fires, or 35 percent of all the
attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motorist Killed Due to Curiosity Over Road Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A man who slowed down his car to
poke his nose into a road accident was killed by angry teenagers
in Chon Buri province on Sunday as the man's car blocked their
way.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old unlucky man was shot on his way to Bang Saen, a
seaside resort frequented by Thai holiday makers, by one of a
group of teenagers who were traveling behind him in four other
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The teenagers apparently were angry as the man slowed down his
car and tried to have a better look at a roadside accident, which
caused a minor traffic jam, local newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
The man was chased and shot by the teenagers when he tried to
drive off later. He was found dead when he was sent to a nearby
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Local police are looking for clues to identify the attackers.
</P>
<P>
The traffic jam is a long-standing problem which tortures
travelers in the tropical country, especially in Bangkok and
nearby areas where people seem most likely to lose patient. People
driving cars on congested routes are advised to avoid causing any
inconvenience to others on the traffic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
