<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Protects Rights of Workers in Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government is looking at
ways to protect the rights of workers who lose their jobs when
foreign investors wind down their businesses in Thailand or move
to other countries.
</P>
<P>
According to a government source, state agencies responsible
for labor have been slow in some cases to enforce regulations,
resulting in foreign investors leaving the country without paying
adequate compensation to workers.
</P>
<P>
The Labor and Social Welfare Ministry has proposed an ad hoc
committee to solve such problems. The committee would be chaired
by deputy prime minister Sukavich Rangsitpol who overseas the
ministry with 14 representatives from related state agencies.
</P>
<P>
The committee will look to tackle problems over the long-term,
including amending regulations in order to strengthen the rights
of employees.
</P>
<P>
At least 2,500 factories owned by foreign investors are
operating in Thailand, but some are relocating to lower-wage
countries.
</P>
<P>
Staporn Kavitanon, secretary-general of the Board of Investment
(BOI), was quoted today by the local press as saying that labor
problems could grow more serious during the current economic
slowdown as some factories are relocating.
</P>
<P>
The BOI already has its own committee to ensure that labor
issues are addressed at factories that have BOI privileges, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
