<HEADLINE> Overseas Banks Active In China's Money Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Overseas banks which are licensed
to deal in the local currency in Shanghai have become active
participants in China's inter-bank money market.
</P>
<P>
Total lendings by six overseas banks had reached 269 million
yuan by the end of last month, according to the Shanghai-based
fund center.
</P>
<P>
The first lending by the banks occurred in early April when
Japan's Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi put ten million yuan into the
money market.
</P>
<P>
Limited assets in the Renminbi yuan made it difficult for such
overseas banks to grant huge loans to overseas-funded ventures,
and they now are mainly involved in banking services like
accounts opening, depositing, settlement and fund-raising
activities in the money market, said Huang Jinrong, deputy
president of the Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corp.
</P>
<P>
But analysts said that, judging from their activities on the
money market, the banks have already demonstrated their ability to
handle funds efficiently. (8.3 yuan = one US dollar) 
</P>
</TEXT>
