<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Wants Resolution of Kashmir Issue: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif says Pakistan wants good relations with India by resolving
the outstanding issues between them including the Kashmir problem.
</P>
<P>
"People want good relations but also want resolution of the
problems," he said in an interview with the India-based EL-TV
network telecast which was published on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said restoration of trade links between Pakistan and India
would benefit both countries.
</P>
<P>
"But we have to carry people with us, who also want progress on
Kashmir and other issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif urged the need for easing visa restrictions by both
Islamabad and New Delhi. "I can assure you from my side, there
will be no problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
The hot-line between the prime ministers of the two countries
would soon be installed and then "we can talk with each other and
sort out the matters on personal level," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
He also called for withdrawal of Indian troops from the
Indian-occupied Jammu and Kashmir and suggested a cut in the
defense budgets of both India and Pakistan "through a mutual
agreement."
</P>
<P>
"I have asked the Indian Prime Minister (Inder Kumar Gujral)
that troops should be withdrawn from Kashmir as a first gesture
which will help in building an atmosphere of trust," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif conceded that there are limitations on both sides.
</P>
<P>
"I can understand the limitations of Mr Gujral, but I too have
got my own limitations. I found Mr Gujral a very nice person and I
hope he will respond positively."
</P>
<P>
When asked whether Islamabad would propose a cut in defense
expenditures during bilateral talks with New Delhi, Sharif said,
"Time will come for it."
</P>
<P>
But he added that it could be done only after progress was made
on other issues, "this can be done after confidence is restored".
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan and India have had a history of "hostilities,
tension, and confrontation spread over fifty years," he said. "We
expect improvement in relations once this temperature is lowered."
</P>
<P>
"We must get over the hangovers of past animosity," he said.
</P>
<P>
While expressing the hope that the next round of foreign
secretary-level talks (scheduled for June 19-22 in Islamabad) will
help in improving bilateral relations, Sharif said, "It would not
be in the interest of the two countries to talk without keeping
the Kashmir issue on the agenda."
</P>
<P>
Answering a question, he said Pakistan wanted to establish
trade links with India on the bilateral level as well as through
the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC).
</P>
<P>
"We must come out of the atmosphere of confrontation, we should
learn lesson from the past," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility of his visit to India, Sharif said he would
undertake the visit "if need arises so."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
