<DOCNO> XIE19970609.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Sees New Economic Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Jiangsu province in east China has
started to experience another round of economic boom as it
recovers from four years of stagnation.
</P>
<P>
The average economic increase is expected to be 13.5 percent
through to the end of the century, as compared to the 12 percent
set for the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), says Xiao Jinghua, a
senior statistician in the province.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output value increased by 12.4 percent in April,
compared with 5.9 percent in January, and the average increase
rate stood at 10.6 percent for the first four months, with profits
up 15.7 percent, and consumer retail prices up only 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The GDP accounted for 8.93 of the national total during that
period, while industrial added value made up 9.7 percent of the
national total, ranking first in the country.
</P>
<P>
Local economists attribute the good outlook in economic
development to an improved infrastructure, steady growth in
agriculture, stable prices, and the growing service sector.
</P>
<P>
Through to the next century, Jiangsu will focus on new economic
growth areas, such as machinery, electronics, automobile and
chemical industries, that will have an average increase of more
than 17 percent in industrial added value.
</P>
<P>
The province has designated 30 key enterprises in these fields
and is making an effort to get 10 billion US dollars in overseas
investment to improve them in four or five years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
