<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal Zhejiang Garners Land from Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Zhejiang province in east China
has made remarkable headway in an ambitious decades-long program
to extend its 1,900-km coastline further offshore, in a major bid
to transform waters into land.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1950s, the province has farmed 1,550 sq kilometers
(equal to 155,000 ha) of land in its coastal waters, including
66,000 ha of cultivated land.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 45 million crammed into 110,000 square
kilometers of land, Zhejiang averages a per-capita cultivated land
space of only 0.03 ha.
</P>
<P>
The created "continent" has not only been turned into vegetable
yards and cotton fields, but also is the site for dozens of
infrastructural facilities and thousands of township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Newly-formed coastal land, which accounts for only 1.4 percent
of the total land area in Zhejiang, is now a leader in the
economic growth in local economy with a GDP of 60 billion yuan in
1996, 14 percent of the province's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
