<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Company Scents Big Profits in Edible Oils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Singapore joint venture
company to make edible oils has been set up in Yantai, a seaport
in Shandong Province in east China, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The venture, involving an investment of about 30 million US
dollars, began production over the weekend. The company, Thian
Sheng Edible Oil (Yantai) Ltd, plans to achieve annual sales of
one billion yuan (120 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The paper quotes Wang Shaojian, president of the company as
saying that besides a focus on the domestic market, the company
will endeavour to tap the overseas market. He also predicted the
company's export volume will top 50 percent of total annual output.
</P>
<P>
Tan Sook, director of Singapore-Shandong Business Council said
that Shandong is a treasure island for Singapore investors, who
will mainly invest in infrastructure of power plants, roads,
bridges, communications, food processing, electronics and
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Tan also said that Singapore investment in Shandong witnessed a
big jump by the end of 1995. China had become the ninth biggest
overseas market for Singapore business.
</P>
<P>
Singapore focuses its investment on China's coastal regions and
has obtained fruitful results, the paper says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
