<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kankkunen Leads Acropolis Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Four-time world champion Juha
Kankkunen, driving a Ford Escort, jumped to a 27-second lead after
the first stage of the Acropolis Rally on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Kankkunen's compatriot, reigning world champion Tommi Makinen,
was level second with Briton Richard Burns after the day's series
of specials in the eighth world championship event of the year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Colin McRae's rally ended after less than half an hour
as he crashed out during the second special.
</P>
<P>
The Scot, who had earlier finished joint fastest with Spain's
Carlos Sainz in the first special, damaged his Subaru's steering
wheel column after hitting a rock.
</P>
<P>
Mechanics were unable to repair the damage to the car of the
1995 world champion, who won the Acropolis last year.
</P>
<P>
Kankkunen, a winner of this rally in 1986 and 1991, started
steadily before cranking up the speed after the third special. In
the sixth, he took advantage of a crash by then-leader Kenneth
Eriksson of Sweden, who damaged his Subaru's suspension and lost
11 minutes to the Finn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
