<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatian President Takes Train To Vukovar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A special train aboard with Croatian
President Franjo Tudjman went to Vukovar, eastern Slavonia, on
Sunday, marking a symbolic return of Croatia to its Danube
borders.
</P>
<P>
"The Train For Vukovar-Peace Train" consisted of 21 carriages,
representing all counties of Croatia, and carried 2,000 guests
including senior government officials, representatives of various
circles and ambassadors of foreign missions in Zagreb.
</P>
<P>
Vukovar is the main town of eastern Slavonia which was
controlled by Serb rebels fighting against Croatia's independence,
but will return to Croatia in the middle of next month under an
agreement reached between Zagreb and local Serbs in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Before starting the trip, Tudjman told a rally in the Zagreb
railway station that by riding this train, "we are completing the
historical victory of the Croatian freedom, of creation of the
independent, sovereign and democratic Croatia".
</P>
<P>
This also was a train of reconciliation with Serbs who would
like to stay and recognize Croatia, Tudjman said, adding that the
Croatian government would guarantee them civil and ethnic rights.
</P>
<P>
The train was greeted in Vukovar by representatives of local
Serbs as well as UN administrator of eastern Slavonia Jacques
Klein.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the welcoming ceremony, Klein called for efforts to
be redoubled in helping Serb displaced persons to return their
homes elsewhere in Croatia so that Croat refugees who had fled the
region could be able to come back.
</P>
<P>
When the train was on its way back to Zagreb, it was stoned by
a group of "local Serb extremists", with one window broken but no
one hurt, according to local press reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
